# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: computer-architecture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] In computer architecture, a **branch predictor** is a digital circuit that tries to guess which way a branch (e.g., an if–then–else structure) will go before this is known definitively.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The purpose of the branch predictor is to improve the flow in the instruction pipeline.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Branch predictors play a critical role in achieving high performance in many modern pipelined microprocessor architectures.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Two-way branching is usually implemented with a conditional jump instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A conditional jump can either be "taken" and jump to a different place in program memory, or it can be "not taken" and continue execution immediately after the conditional jump.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] It is not known for certain whether a conditional jump will be taken or not taken until the condition has been calculated and the conditional jump has passed the execution stage in the instruction pipeline (see fig.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Without branch prediction, the processor would have to wait until the conditional jump instruction has passed the execute stage before the next instruction can enter the fetch stage in the pipeline.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The branch predictor attempts to avoid this waste of time by trying to guess whether the conditional jump is most likely to be taken or not taken.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The branch that is guessed to be the most likely is then fetched and speculatively executed.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] If it is later detected that the guess was wrong, then the speculatively executed or partially executed instructions are discarded and the pipeline starts over with the correct branch, incurring a delay.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The time that is wasted in case of a **branch misprediction** is equal to the number of stages in the pipeline from the fetch stage to the execute stage.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Modern microprocessors tend to have quite long pipelines so that the misprediction delay is between 10 and 20 clock cycles.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] As a result, making a pipeline longer increases the need for a more advanced branch predictor.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The first time a conditional jump instruction is encountered, there is not much information to base a prediction on.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] However, the branch predictor keeps records of whether or not branches are taken, so when it encounters a conditional jump that has been seen several times before, it can base the prediction on the recorded history.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The branch predictor may, for example, recognize that the conditional jump is taken more often than not, or that it is taken every second time.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Branch prediction is not the same as branch target prediction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Branch prediction attempts to guess whether a conditional jump will be taken or not.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Branch target prediction attempts to guess the target of a taken conditional or unconditional jump before it is computed by decoding and executing the instruction itself.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Branch prediction and branch target prediction are often combined into the same circuitry.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Static prediction is the simplest branch prediction technique because it does not rely on information about the dynamic history of code executing.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Instead, it predicts the outcome of a branch based solely on the branch instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Early implementations of SPARC and MIPS (two of the first commercial RISC architectures) used single-direction static branch prediction: they always predict that a conditional jump will not be taken, so they always fetch the next sequential instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Only when the branch or jump is evaluated and found to be taken, does the instruction pointer get set to a non-sequential address.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Both CPUs fetch instructions in one cycle and evaluate branches in the decode stage.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] As a result, the branch target recurrence is two cycles long, and the machine always fetches the instruction immediately after any taken branch.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Both architectures define branch delay slots in order to utilize these fetched instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A more-advanced form of static prediction assumes that backward branches will be taken and forward branches will not.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] (A backward branch is one that has a target address that is lower than its own address.) This rule increases prediction accuracy in loops, which can be constructed with a backward branch at the end that is mostly taken, or a forward branch at the beginning that is mostly not taken.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] With processors that use this prediction method, ordering the instructions can maximize branch-prediction accuracy.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The RISC-V ISA recommends that software written for RISC-V harts (hardware threads), or generated to run on RISC-V harts, be optimized with the assumption that backward branches are taken and forward branches are not.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Some processors accept branch-prediction hints that override the static prediction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The Intel Pentium 4 and Pentium 4E accept branch-prediction hints as prefixes.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] In the presence of dynamic prediction, static prediction offers almost no benefit, and overriding the static prediction helps even less.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Intel's subsequent Pentium M and Core2 processors ignore branch-prediction hint prefixes.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] No x86 manufacturer has re-introduced prediction hints.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Dynamic branch predictors naturally fall back on static branch prediction when they have no cached information (such as the first time a given branch is encountered).
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Both the Motorola MPC7450 (G4e) and the Intel Pentium 4 fall back on static prediction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] In static prediction, all decisions are made at compile time, before the execution of the program.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Dynamic branch prediction uses information about taken or not-taken branches gathered at run-time to predict the outcome of a branch.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Random branch prediction means taking a random guess at whether a branch will be taken, each time it is executed.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The cost for a pseudorandom number generator is low compared to other techniques.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Random prediction guarantees a 50% correct prediction rate that cannot be increased or reduced by any means.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] (And it makes timing even more nondeterministic or unpredictable than other methods.) Static branch prediction (assuming forward branches are taken and backward branches are not) predicts each branch with an accuracy ranging from 0% to 100%, with the overall success rate somewhere in-between.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Unoptimized code is very likely to run with better than 50% prediction success; even 90% is likely.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] If the compiler does some instruction reordering, it makes the correct branch prediction rate higher than for unoptimized code.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Static branch prediction long ago surpassed random branch prediction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Dynamic branch prediction has surpassed static branch prediction and is commonplace, despite the added complexity.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Some superscalar processors (MIPS R8000, Alpha 21264, and Alpha 21464 (EV8)) fetch each line of instructions with a pointer to the next line.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] This next-line predictor handles branch target prediction as well as branch direction prediction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] When a next-line predictor points to aligned groups of 2, 4, or 8 instructions, the branch target will usually not be the first instruction fetched, and so the initial instructions fetched are wasted.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Assuming for simplicity, a uniform distribution of branch targets, 0.5, 1.5, and 3.5 instructions fetched are discarded, respectively.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Since the branch itself will generally not be the last instruction in an aligned group, instructions after the taken branch (or its delay slot) will be discarded.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Once again, assuming a uniform distribution of branch instruction placements, 0.5, 1.5, and 3.5 instructions fetched are discarded.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The discarded instructions at the branch and destination lines add up to nearly a complete fetch cycle, even for a single-cycle next-line predictor.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A 1-bit saturating counter (essentially a flip-flop) records the last outcome of the branch.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] This is the most simple version of dynamic branch predictor possible, although it is not very accurate.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] When a branch is evaluated, the corresponding state machine is updated.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Branches evaluated as not taken change the state toward strongly not taken, and branches evaluated as taken change the state toward strongly taken.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The advantage of the two-bit counter scheme over a one-bit scheme is that a conditional jump has to deviate twice from what it has done most in the past before the prediction changes.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] For example, a loop-closing conditional jump is mispredicted once rather than twice.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The original, non-MMX Intel Pentium processor uses a saturating counter, though with an imperfect implementation.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] On the SPEC'89 benchmarks, very large bimodal predictors saturate at 93.5% correct, once every branch maps to a unique counter.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The predictor table is indexed with the instruction address bits, so that the processor can fetch a prediction for every instruction before the instruction is decoded.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The Two-Level Branch Predictor, also referred to as Correlation-Based Branch Predictor, uses a two-dimensional table of counters, also called "Pattern History Table".
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] If an `if` statement is executed three times, the decision made on the third execution might depend upon whether the previous two were taken or not.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] In such scenarios, a two-level adaptive predictor works more efficiently than a saturation counter.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Conditional jumps that are taken every second time or have some other regularly recurring pattern are not predicted well by the saturating counter.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A two-level adaptive predictor remembers the history of the last n occurrences of the branch and uses one saturating counter for each of the possible 2n history patterns.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] This means that the last two occurrences of the branch are stored in a two-bit shift register.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] This branch history register can have four different binary values, 00, 01, 10, and 11, where zero means "not taken" and one means "taken".
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A pattern history table contains four entries per branch, one for each of the 22 = 4 possible branch histories, and each entry in the table contains a two-bit saturating counter of the same type as in figure 2 for each branch.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The branch history register is used for choosing which of the four saturating counters to use.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] If the history is 00, then the first counter is used; if the history is 11, then the last of the four counters is used.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Assume, for example, that a conditional jump is taken every third time.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] In this case, entry number 00 in the pattern history table will go to state "strongly taken", indicating that after two zeroes comes a one.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Entry number 01 will go to state "strongly not taken", indicating that after 01 comes a zero.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The same is the case with entry number 10, while entry number 11 is never used because there are never two consecutive ones.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The general rule for a two-level adaptive predictor with an n-bit history is that it can predict any repetitive sequence with any period if all n-bit sub-sequences are different.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The advantage of the two-level adaptive predictor is that it can quickly learn to predict an arbitrary repetitive pattern.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Yeh and Yale Patt at the University of Michigan.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Since the initial publication in 1991, this method has become very popular, with it being used for later Pentium processors like the Pentium MMX.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Variants of this prediction method are used in most modern microprocessors.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A two-level branch predictor where the second level is replaced with a neural network has been proposed.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A local branch predictor has a separate history buffer for each conditional jump instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] It may use a two-level adaptive predictor.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The history buffer is separate for each conditional jump instruction, while the pattern history table may be separate as well or it may be shared between all conditional jumps.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The Intel Pentium MMX, Pentium II, and Pentium III have local branch predictors with a local 4-bit history and a local pattern history table with 16 entries for each conditional jump.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] On the SPEC'89 benchmarks, very large local predictors saturate at 97.1% correct.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A global branch predictor does not keep a separate history record for each conditional jump.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Instead it keeps a shared history of all conditional jumps.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The advantage of a shared history is that any correlation between different conditional jumps is part of making the predictions.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The disadvantage is that the history is diluted by irrelevant information if the different conditional jumps are uncorrelated, and that the history buffer may not include any bits from the same branch if there are many other branches in between.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] This scheme is better than the saturating counter scheme only for large table sizes, and it is rarely as good as local prediction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The history buffer must be longer in order to make a good prediction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The size of the pattern history table grows exponentially with the size of the history buffer.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Hence, the big pattern history table must be shared among all conditional jumps.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A two-level adaptive predictor with globally shared history buffer and pattern history table is called a "gshare" predictor if it xors the global history and branch PC, and "gselect" if it concatenates them.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Global branch prediction is used in AMD processors, and in Intel Pentium M, Core, Core 2, and Silvermont-based Atom processors.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] An alloyed branch predictor combines the local and global prediction principles by concatenating local and global branch histories, possibly with some bits from the program counter as well.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Tests indicate that the VIA Nano processor may be using this technique.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] An agree predictor is a two-level adaptive predictor with globally shared history buffer and pattern history table, and an additional local saturating counter.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The outputs of the local and the global predictors are XORed with each other to give the final prediction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The purpose is to reduce contentions in the pattern history table where two branches with opposite prediction happen to share the same entry in the pattern history table.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A hybrid predictor, also called combined predictor, implements more than one prediction mechanism.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The final prediction is based either on a meta-predictor that remembers which of the predictors has made the best predictions in the past, or a majority vote function based on an odd number of different predictors.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Scott McFarling proposed combined branch prediction in his 1993 paper.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] On the SPEC'89 benchmarks, such a predictor is about as good as the local predictor.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Predictors like gshare use multiple table entries to track the behavior of any particular branch.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] This multiplication of entries makes it much more likely that two branches will map to the same table entry (a situation called aliasing), which in turn makes it much more likely that prediction accuracy will suffer for those branches.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Once you have multiple predictors, it is beneficial to arrange that each predictor will have different aliasing patterns, so that it is more likely that at least one predictor will have no aliasing.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Combined predictors with different indexing functions for the different predictors are called *gskew* predictors, and are analogous to skewed associative caches used for data and instruction caching.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A conditional jump that controls a loop is best predicted with a special loop predictor.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A conditional jump in the bottom of a loop that repeats N times will be taken N-1 times and then not taken once.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] If the conditional jump is placed at the top of the loop, it will be not taken N-1 times and then taken once.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A conditional jump that goes many times one way and then the other way once is detected as having loop behavior.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Such a conditional jump can be predicted easily with a simple counter.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A loop predictor is part of a hybrid predictor where a meta-predictor detects whether the conditional jump has loop behavior.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] An indirect jump instruction can choose among more than two branches.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Some processors have specialized indirect branch predictors.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Newer processors from Intel and AMD can predict indirect branches by using a two-level adaptive predictor.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] This kind of instruction contributes more than one bit to the history buffer.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The zEC12 and later z/Architecture processors from IBM support a BRANCH PREDICTION PRELOAD instruction that can preload the branch predictor entry for a given instruction with a branch target address constructed by adding the contents of a general-purpose register to an immediate displacement value.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Processors without this mechanism will simply predict an indirect jump to go to the same target as it did last time.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] A function will normally return to where it is called from.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The return instruction is an indirect jump that reads its target address from the call stack.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Many microprocessors have a separate prediction mechanism for return instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] This mechanism is based on a so-called *return stack buffer*, which is a local mirror of the call stack.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The size of the return stack buffer is typically 4–16 entries.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The trade-off between fast branch prediction and good branch prediction is sometimes dealt with by having two branch predictors.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The first branch predictor is fast and simple.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The second branch predictor, which is slower, more complex, and with bigger tables, will override a possibly wrong prediction made by the first predictor.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The Alpha 21264 and Alpha EV8 microprocessors used a fast single-cycle next-line predictor to handle the branch target recurrence and provide a simple and fast branch prediction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Because the next-line predictor is so inaccurate, and the branch resolution recurrence takes so long, both cores have two-cycle secondary branch predictors that can override the prediction of the next-line predictor at the cost of a single lost fetch cycle.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The Intel Core i7 has two branch target buffers and possibly two or more branch predictors.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Machine learning for branch prediction using LVQ and multilayer perceptrons, called "neural branch prediction", was proposed by Lucian Vintan (Lucian Blaga University of Sibiu).
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] One year later he developed the perceptron branch predictor.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The neural branch predictor research was developed much further by Daniel Jimenez.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] In 2001, the first perceptron predictor was presented that was feasible to implement in hardware.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The first commercial implementation of a perceptron branch predictor was in AMD's Piledriver microarchitecture.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The main advantage of the neural predictor is its ability to exploit long histories while requiring only linear resource growth.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Classical predictors require exponential resource growth.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Jimenez reports a global improvement of 5.7% over a McFarling-style hybrid predictor.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] He also used a gshare/perceptron overriding hybrid predictors.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The main disadvantage of the perceptron predictor is its high latency.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Even after taking advantage of high-speed arithmetic tricks, the computation latency is relatively high compared to the clock period of many modern microarchitectures.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] In order to reduce the prediction latency, Jimenez proposed in 2003 the *fast-path neural predictor*, where the perceptron predictor chooses its weights according to the current branch's path, rather than according to the branch's PC.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Many other researchers developed this concept (A.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Most of the state-of-the-art branch predictors are using a perceptron predictor (see Intel's "Championship Branch Prediction Competition").
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Intel already implements this idea in one of the IA-64's simulators (2003).
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The AMD Ryzen multi-core processor's Infinity Fabric and the Samsung Exynos processors include perceptron-based neural branch predictors.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The IBM 7030 Stretch, designed in the late 1950s, pre-executes all unconditional branches and any conditional branches that depended on the index registers.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] For other conditional branches, the first two production models implemented predict untaken; subsequent models were changed to implement predictions based on the current values of the indicator bits (corresponding to today's condition codes).
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The Stretch designers had considered static hint bits in the branch instructions early in the project but decided against them.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Misprediction recovery was provided by the lookahead unit on Stretch, and part of Stretch's reputation for less-than-stellar performance was blamed on the time required for misprediction recovery.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Subsequent IBM large computer designs did not use branch prediction with speculative execution until the IBM 3090 in 1985.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Two-bit predictors were introduced by Tom McWilliams and Curt Widdoes in 1977 for the Lawrence Livermore National Lab S-1 supercomputer and independently by Jim Smith in 1979 at CDC.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Microprogrammed processors, popular from the 1960s to the 1980s and beyond, took multiple cycles per instruction, and generally did not require branch prediction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] However, in addition to the IBM 3090, there are several other examples of microprogrammed designs that incorporated branch prediction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The Burroughs B4900, a microprogrammed COBOL machine released around 1982, was pipelined and used branch prediction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The B4900 branch prediction history state is stored back into the in-memory instructions during program execution.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The B4900 implements 4-state branch prediction by using 4 semantically equivalent branch opcodes to represent each branch operator type.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The opcode used indicated the history of that particular branch instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] If the hardware determines that the branch prediction state of a particular branch needs to be updated, it rewrites the opcode with the semantically equivalent opcode that hinted the proper history.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] US patent 4,435,756 and others were granted on this scheme.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The DEC VAX 9000, announced in 1989, is both microprogrammed and pipelined, and performs branch prediction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The first commercial RISC processors, the MIPS R2000 and R3000 and the earlier SPARC processors, do only trivial "not-taken" branch prediction.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Because they use branch delay slots, fetched just one instruction per cycle, and execute in-order, there is no performance loss.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The later R4000 uses the same trivial "not-taken" branch prediction, and loses two cycles to each taken branch because the branch resolution recurrence is four cycles long.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Branch prediction became more important with the introduction of pipelined superscalar processors like the Intel Pentium, DEC Alpha 21064, the MIPS R8000, and the IBM POWER series.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] These processors all rely on one-bit or simple bimodal predictors.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The DEC Alpha 21264 (EV6) uses a next-line predictor overridden by a combined local predictor and global predictor, where the combining choice is made by a bimodal predictor.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The AMD K8 has a combined bimodal and global predictor, where the combining choice is another bimodal predictor.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] This processor caches the base and choice bimodal predictor counters in bits of the L2 cache otherwise used for ECC.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] As a result, it has effectively very large base and choice predictor tables, and parity rather than ECC on instructions in the L2 cache.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The parity design is sufficient, since any instruction suffering a parity error can be invalidated and refetched from memory.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The Alpha 21464 (EV8, cancelled late in design) had a minimum branch misprediction penalty of 14 cycles.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] It was to use a complex but fast next-line predictor overridden by a combined bimodal and majority-voting predictor.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The majority vote was between the bimodal and two gskew predictors.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] In 2018 a catastrophic security vulnerability called Spectre was made public by Google's Project Zero and other researchers.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] Affecting virtually all modern CPUs, the vulnerability involves priming the branch predictors so another process (or the kernel) will mispredict a branch and use secret data as an array index, evicting one of the attacker's cache lines.
[src:computer-architecture/branch-predictor] The attacker can time access to their own array to find out which one, turning this CPU internal (microarchitectural) state into a value the attacker can save which has information about values they could not read directly.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] A **central processing unit** (**CPU**), also known as a **central processor**, **main processor**, or simply **processor**, is the primary processor in a given computer.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Its electronic circuitry executes instructions of a computer program, such as arithmetic, logic, controlling, and input/output (I/O) operations.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] This role contrasts with that of external components, such as main memory and I/O circuitry, and specialized coprocessors such as graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The form, design, and implementation of CPUs have changed over time, but their fundamental operation remains almost unchanged.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Modern CPUs devote a lot of semiconductor area to caches and instruction-level parallelism to increase performance and to CPU modes to support operating systems and virtualization.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Most modern CPUs are implemented on integrated circuit (IC) microprocessors, with one or more CPUs on a single IC chip.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Microprocessor chips with multiple CPUs are called *multi-core processors* (*MCPs*).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The individual physical CPUs, called *processor cores*, can also be multithreaded to support CPU-level multithreading.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] An IC that contains a CPU may also contain memory, peripheral interfaces, and other components of a computer; such integrated devices are variously called microcontrollers or systems on chip (SoCs).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Early computers such as the ENIAC had to be physically rewired to perform different tasks, which caused these machines to be called "fixed-program computers".
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The "central processing unit" term has been in use since as early as 1955.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Since the term "CPU" is generally defined as a device for software (computer program) execution, the earliest devices that could rightly be called CPUs came with the advent of the stored-program computer.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The idea of a stored-program computer had already been present in the design of John Presper Eckert and John William Mauchly's ENIAC, but was initially omitted so that it could be finished sooner.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] On June 30, 1945, before ENIAC was made, mathematician John von Neumann distributed a paper entitled *First Draft of a Report on the EDVAC*.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] It was the outline of a stored-program computer that would eventually be completed in August 1949.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] EDVAC was designed to perform a certain number of instructions (or operations) of various types.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Significantly, the programs written for EDVAC were to be stored in high-speed computer memory rather than specified by the physical wiring of the computer.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] This overcame a severe limitation of ENIAC, which was the considerable time and effort required to reconfigure the computer to perform a new task.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] With von Neumann's design, the program that EDVAC ran could be changed simply by changing the contents of the memory.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] EDVAC was not the first stored-program computer; the Manchester Baby, which was a small-scale experimental stored-program computer, ran its first program on 21 June 1948 and the Manchester Mark 1 ran its first program during the night of 16–17 June 1949.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Early CPUs were custom designs used as part of a larger and sometimes distinctive computer.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] However, this method of designing custom CPUs for a particular application has largely given way to the development of multi-purpose processors produced in large quantities.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] This standardization began in the era of discrete transistor mainframes and minicomputers, and has rapidly accelerated with the popularization of the integrated circuit (IC).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The IC has allowed increasingly complex CPUs to be designed and manufactured to tolerances on the order of nanometers.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Both the miniaturization and standardization of CPUs have increased the presence of digital devices in modern life far beyond the limited application of dedicated computing machines.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Modern microprocessors appear in electronic devices ranging from automobiles to cellphones, and sometimes even in toys.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] While von Neumann is most often credited with the design of the stored-program computer because of his design of EDVAC, and the design became known as the von Neumann architecture, others before him, such as Konrad Zuse, had suggested and implemented similar ideas.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The so-called Harvard architecture of the Harvard Mark I, which was completed before EDVAC, also used a stored-program design using punched paper tape rather than electronic memory.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The key difference between the two is that Harvard architecture separates the storage and treatment of CPU instructions and data, whereas von Neumann architecture uses the same memory space for both.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Most modern CPUs are primarily von Neumann in design, but CPUs with the Harvard architecture are seen as well, especially in embedded applications; for instance, the Atmel AVR microcontrollers are Harvard-architecture processors.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Prior to the invention of the transistor, relays and vacuum tubes (thermionic tubes) were commonly used as switching elements; a useful computer requires thousands or tens of thousands of switching devices.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The overall speed of a system is dependent on the speed of the switches.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Vacuum-tube computers such as EDVAC tended to average eight hours between failures, whereas relay computers—such as the slower but earlier Harvard Mark I—failed very rarely.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] In the end, tube-based CPUs became dominant because the significant speed advantages afforded generally outweighed the reliability problems.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Most of these early synchronous CPUs ran at low clock rates compared to modern microelectronic designs.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Clock signal frequencies ranging from 100 kHz to 4 MHz were very common at this time, limited largely by the speed of the switching devices they were built with.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The design complexity of CPUs increased as various technologies facilitated the building of smaller and more reliable electronic devices.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The first such improvement came with the advent of the transistor.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Transistorized CPUs during the 1950s and 1960s no longer had to be built out of bulky, unreliable, and fragile switching elements, like vacuum tubes and relays.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] With this improvement, more complex and reliable CPUs were built onto one or several printed circuit boards containing discrete (individual) components.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] In 1964, IBM introduced its IBM System/360 computer architecture that was used in a series of computers capable of running the same programs with different speeds and performances.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] This was significant at a time when most electronic computers were incompatible with one another, even those made by the same manufacturer.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] To facilitate this improvement, IBM used the concept of a microprogram (often called "microcode"), which still sees widespread use in modern CPUs.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The System/360 architecture was so popular that it dominated the mainframe computer market for decades and left a legacy that is continued by similar modern computers like the IBM zSeries.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] In 1965, Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) introduced another influential computer aimed at the scientific and research markets—the PDP-8.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Transistor-based computers had several distinct advantages over their predecessors.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Aside from facilitating increased reliability and lower power consumption, transistors also allowed CPUs to operate at much higher speeds because of the short switching time of a transistor in comparison to a tube or relay.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The increased reliability and dramatically increased speed of the switching elements, which were almost exclusively transistors by this time; CPU clock rates in the tens of megahertz were easily obtained during this period.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Additionally, while discrete transistor and IC CPUs were in heavy usage, new high-performance designs like single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) vector processors began to appear.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] These early experimental designs later gave rise to the era of specialized supercomputers like those made by Cray Inc and Fujitsu Ltd.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] During this period, a method of manufacturing many interconnected transistors in a compact space was developed.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The integrated circuit (IC) allowed a large number of transistors to be manufactured on a single semiconductor-based die, or "chip".
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] At first, only very basic non-specialized digital circuits such as NOR gates were miniaturized into ICs.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] CPUs based on these "building block" ICs are generally referred to as "small-scale integration" (SSI) devices.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] SSI ICs, such as the ones used in the Apollo Guidance Computer, usually contained up to a few dozen transistors.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] To build an entire CPU out of SSI ICs required thousands of individual chips, but still consumed much less space and power than earlier discrete transistor designs.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] IBM's System/370, follow-on to the System/360, used SSI ICs rather than Solid Logic Technology discrete-transistor modules.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] DEC's PDP-8/I and KI10 PDP-10 also switched from the individual transistors used by the PDP-8 and KA PDP-10 to SSI ICs, and their extremely popular PDP-11 line was originally built with SSI ICs, but was eventually implemented with LSI components once these became practical.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Lee Boysel published influential articles, including a 1967 "manifesto", which described how to build the equivalent of a 32-bit mainframe computer from a relatively small number of large-scale integration circuits (LSI).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The only way to build LSI chips, which are chips with a hundred or more gates, was to build them using a metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) semiconductor manufacturing process (either PMOS logic, NMOS logic, or CMOS logic).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] However, some companies continued to build processors out of bipolar transistor–transistor logic (TTL) chips because bipolar junction transistors were faster than MOS chips up until the 1970s (a few companies such as Datapoint continued to build processors out of TTL chips until the early 1980s).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] In the 1960s, MOS ICs were slower and initially considered useful only in applications that required low power.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Following the development of silicon-gate MOS technology by Federico Faggin at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1968, MOS ICs largely replaced bipolar TTL as the standard chip technology in the late 1970s.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] As the microelectronic technology advanced, an increasing number of transistors were placed on ICs, decreasing the number of individual ICs needed for a complete CPU.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] MSI and LSI ICs increased transistor counts to hundreds, and then thousands.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] By 1968, the number of ICs required to build a complete CPU had been reduced to 24 ICs of eight different types, with each IC containing roughly 1000 MOSFETs.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] In stark contrast with its SSI and MSI predecessors, the first LSI implementation of the PDP-11 contained a CPU composed of only four LSI integrated circuits.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Since microprocessors were first introduced they have almost completely overtaken all other central processing unit implementation methods.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The first commercially available microprocessor, made in 1971, was the Intel 4004.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The Intel 4004 was one of the first consumer-facing CPUs integrating arithmetic logic unit, control unit, and register unit on a chip.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The first widely used microprocessor, made in 1974, was the Intel 8080.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Mainframe and minicomputer manufacturers of the time launched proprietary IC development programs to upgrade their older computer architectures, and eventually produced instruction set compatible microprocessors that were backward-compatible with their older hardware and software.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Combined with the advent and eventual success of the ubiquitous personal computer, the term *CPU* is now applied almost exclusively to microprocessors.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Several CPUs (denoted *cores*) can be combined in a single processing chip.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Previous generations of CPUs were implemented as discrete components and numerous small integrated circuits (ICs) on one or more circuit boards.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Microprocessors, on the other hand, are CPUs manufactured on a very small number of ICs; usually just one.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The overall smaller CPU size, as a result of being implemented on a single die, means faster switching time because of physical factors like decreased gate parasitic capacitance.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] This has allowed synchronous microprocessors to have clock rates ranging from tens of megahertz to several gigahertz.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Additionally, the ability to construct exceedingly small transistors on an IC has increased the complexity and number of transistors in a single CPU many fold.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] This widely observed trend is described by Moore's law, which had proven to be a fairly accurate predictor of the growth of CPU (and other IC) complexity until 2016.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] While the complexity, size, construction and general form of CPUs have changed enormously since 1950, the basic design and function has not changed much at all.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Almost all common CPUs today can be very accurately described as von Neumann stored-program machines.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] As Moore's law no longer holds, concerns have arisen about the limits of integrated circuit transistor technology.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Extreme miniaturization of electronic gates is causing the effects of phenomena like electromigration and subthreshold leakage to become much more significant.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] These newer concerns are among the many factors causing researchers to investigate new methods of computing such as the quantum computer, as well as to expand the use of parallelism and other methods that extend the usefulness of the classical von Neumann model.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The fundamental operation of most CPUs, regardless of the physical form they take, is to execute a sequence of stored instructions that is called a program.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The instructions to be executed are kept in some kind of computer memory.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Nearly all CPUs follow the fetch, decode and execute steps in their operation, which are collectively known as the instruction cycle.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] After the execution of an instruction, the entire process repeats, with the next instruction cycle normally fetching the next-in-sequence instruction because of the incremented value in the program counter.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] If a jump instruction was executed, the program counter will be modified to contain the address of the instruction that was jumped to and program execution continues normally.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] In more complex CPUs, multiple instructions can be fetched, decoded and executed simultaneously.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] This section describes what is generally referred to as the "classic RISC pipeline", which is quite common among the simple CPUs used in many electronic devices (often called microcontrollers).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] It largely ignores the important role of CPU cache, and therefore the access stage of the pipeline.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Some instructions manipulate the program counter rather than producing result data directly; such instructions are generally called "jumps" and facilitate program behavior like loops, conditional program execution (through the use of a conditional jump), and existence of functions.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] In some processors, some other instructions change the state of bits in a "flags" register.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] These flags can be used to influence how a program behaves, since they often indicate the outcome of various operations.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] For example, in such processors a "compare" instruction evaluates two values and sets or clears bits in the flags register to indicate which one is greater or whether they are equal; one of these flags could then be used by a later jump instruction to determine program flow.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Fetch involves retrieving an instruction (which is represented by a number or sequence of numbers) from program memory.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The instruction's location (address) in program memory is determined by the program counter (PC; called the "instruction pointer" in Intel x86 microprocessors), which stores a number that identifies the address of the next instruction to be fetched.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] After an instruction is fetched, the PC is incremented by the length of the instruction so that it will contain the address of the next instruction in the sequence.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Often, the instruction to be fetched must be retrieved from relatively slow memory, causing the CPU to stall while waiting for the instruction to be returned.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] This issue is largely addressed in modern processors by caches and pipeline architectures (see below).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The instruction that the CPU fetches from memory determines what the CPU will do.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] In the decode step, performed by binary decoder circuitry known as the *instruction decoder*, the instruction is converted into signals that control other parts of the CPU.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The way in which the instruction is interpreted is defined by the CPU's instruction set architecture (ISA).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Often, one group of bits (that is, a "field") within the instruction, called the opcode, indicates which operation is to be performed, while the remaining fields usually provide supplemental information required for the operation, such as the operands.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Those operands may be specified as a constant value (called an immediate value), or as the location of a value that may be a processor register or a memory address, as determined by some addressing mode.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] In some CPU designs, the instruction decoder is implemented as a hardwired, unchangeable binary decoder circuit.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] In others, a microprogram is used to translate instructions into sets of CPU configuration signals that are applied sequentially over multiple clock pulses.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] In some cases the memory that stores the microprogram is rewritable, making it possible to change the way in which the CPU decodes instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] After the fetch and decode steps, the execute step is performed.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Depending on the CPU architecture, this may consist of a single action or a sequence of actions.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] During each action, control signals electrically enable or disable various parts of the CPU so they can perform all or part of the desired operation.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] The action is then completed, typically in response to a clock pulse.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] Very often the results are written to an internal CPU register for quick access by subsequent instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] In other cases results may be written to slower, but less expensive and higher capacity main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] For example, if an instruction that performs addition is to be executed, registers containing operands (numbers to be summed) are activated, as are the parts of the arithmetic logic unit (ALU) that perform addition.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] When the clock pulse occurs, the operands flow from the source registers into the ALU, and the sum appears at its output.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] On subsequent clock pulses, other components are enabled (and disabled) to move the output (the sum of the operation) to storage (e.g., a register or memory).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p01] If the resulting sum is too large (i.e., it is larger than the ALU's output word size), an arithmetic overflow flag will be set, influencing the next operation.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Hardwired into a CPU's circuitry is a set of basic operations it can perform, called an instruction set.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Such operations may involve, for example, adding or subtracting two numbers, comparing two numbers, or jumping to a different part of a program.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Each instruction is represented by a unique combination of bits, known as the machine language opcode.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] While processing an instruction, the CPU decodes the opcode (via a binary decoder) into control signals, which orchestrate the behavior of the CPU.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] A complete machine language instruction consists of an opcode and, in many cases, additional bits that specify arguments for the operation (for example, the numbers to be summed in the case of an addition operation).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Going up the complexity scale, a machine language program is a collection of machine language instructions that the CPU executes.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The actual mathematical operation for each instruction is performed by a combinational logic circuit within the CPU's processor known as the arithmetic–logic unit or ALU.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] In general, a CPU executes an instruction by fetching it from memory, using its ALU to perform an operation, and then storing the result to memory.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The control unit (CU) is a component of the CPU that directs the operation of the processor.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] It tells the computer's memory, arithmetic and logic unit and input and output devices how to respond to the instructions that have been sent to the processor.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] It directs the operation of the other units by providing timing and control signals.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Most computer resources are managed by the CU.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] It directs the flow of data between the CPU and the other devices.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] John von Neumann included the control unit as part of the von Neumann architecture.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] In modern computer designs, the control unit is typically an internal part of the CPU with its overall role and operation unchanged since its introduction.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The arithmetic logic unit (ALU) is a digital circuit within the processor that performs integer arithmetic and bitwise logic operations.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The inputs to the ALU are the data words to be operated on (called operands), status information from previous operations, and a code from the control unit indicating which operation to perform.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Depending on the instruction being executed, the operands may come from internal CPU registers, external memory, or constants generated by the ALU itself.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] When all input signals have settled and propagated through the ALU circuitry, the result of the performed operation appears at the ALU's outputs.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The result consists of both a data word, which may be stored in a register or memory, and status information that is typically stored in a special, internal CPU register reserved for this purpose.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Modern CPUs typically contain more than one ALU to improve performance.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The address generation unit (AGU), sometimes also called the address computation unit (ACU), is an execution unit inside the CPU that calculates addresses used by the CPU to access main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] By having address calculations handled by separate circuitry that operates in parallel with the rest of the CPU, the number of CPU cycles required for executing various machine instructions can be reduced, bringing performance improvements.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] While performing various operations, CPUs need to calculate memory addresses required for fetching data from the memory; for example, in-memory positions of array elements must be calculated before the CPU can fetch the data from actual memory locations.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Those address-generation calculations involve different integer arithmetic operations, such as addition, subtraction, modulo operations, or bit shifts.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Often, calculating a memory address involves more than one general-purpose machine instruction, which do not necessarily decode and execute quickly.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] By incorporating an AGU into a CPU design, together with introducing specialized instructions that use the AGU, various address-generation calculations can be offloaded from the rest of the CPU, and can often be executed quickly in a single CPU cycle.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Capabilities of an AGU depend on a particular CPU and its architecture.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Thus, some AGUs implement and expose more address-calculation operations, while some also include more advanced specialized instructions that can operate on multiple operands at a time.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Some CPU architectures include multiple AGUs so more than one address-calculation operation can be executed simultaneously, which brings further performance improvements due to the superscalar nature of advanced CPU designs.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, Intel incorporates multiple AGUs into its Sandy Bridge and Haswell microarchitectures, which increase bandwidth of the CPU memory subsystem by allowing multiple memory-access instructions to be executed in parallel.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Many microprocessors (in smartphones and desktop, laptop, server computers) have a memory management unit (MMU), translating logical addresses into physical RAM addresses, providing memory protection and paging abilities, useful for virtual memory.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The MMU is usually integrated in the processor but in some cases it is in a separate integrated circuit (IC).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Simpler processors, especially microcontrollers, usually do not include an MMU.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] A CPU cache is a memory used by the central processing unit (CPU) of a computer to reduce the average cost (time or energy) to access data from the main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] A cache is a smaller, faster memory, closer to a processor core, which stores copies of the data from frequently used main memory locations.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Most CPUs have different independent caches, usually organized as a hierarchy of several cache levels (L1, L2, L3, L4, etc.).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Each ascending cache level is typically slower but larger than the preceding level with L1 being the fastest and the closest to the CPU.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] At the L1 level there are usually separate instruction and data caches.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Most modern (fast) CPUs (with few specialized exceptions) have multiple levels of CPU caches.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The first CPUs that used a cache had only one level of cache; unlike later level 1 caches, it was not split into L1d (for data) and L1i (for instructions).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Almost all current CPUs with caches have a split L1 cache.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] They also have L2 caches and, for larger processors, L3 caches as well.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The L2 cache is usually not split and acts as a common repository for the already split L1 cache.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Every core of a multi-core processor has a dedicated L2 cache and is usually not shared between the cores.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The L3 cache, and higher-level caches, are shared between the cores and are not split.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] An L4 cache is currently uncommon, and is generally on dynamic random-access memory (DRAM), rather than on static random-access memory (SRAM), on a separate die or chip.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] That was also the case historically with L1, while bigger chips have allowed integration of it and generally all cache levels, with the possible exception of the last level.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Each extra level of cache tends to be bigger and is optimized differently.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Other types of caches exist (that are not counted towards the "cache size" of the most important caches mentioned above), such as the translation lookaside buffer (TLB) that is part of the memory management unit (MMU) that most CPUs have.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Caches are generally sized in powers of two: 2, 8, 16 etc.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] KiB or MiB (for larger non-L1) sizes, although the IBM z13 has a 96 KiB L1 instruction cache.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Most CPUs are synchronous circuits, which means they employ a clock signal to pace their sequential operations.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The clock signal is produced by an external oscillator circuit that generates a consistent number of pulses each second in the form of a periodic square wave.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The frequency of the clock pulses determines the rate at which a CPU executes instructions and, consequently, the faster the clock, the more instructions the CPU will execute each second.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] To ensure proper operation of the CPU, the clock period is longer than the maximum time needed for all signals to propagate (move) through the CPU.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] In setting the clock period to a value well above the worst-case propagation delay, it is possible to design the entire CPU and the way it moves data around the "edges" of the rising and falling clock signal.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This has the advantage of simplifying the CPU significantly, both from a design perspective and a component-count perspective.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] However, it also carries the disadvantage that the entire CPU must wait on its slowest elements, even though some portions of it are much faster.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This limitation has largely been compensated for by various methods of increasing CPU parallelism (see below).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] However, architectural improvements alone do not solve all of the drawbacks of globally synchronous CPUs.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, a clock signal is subject to the delays of any other electrical signal.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Higher clock rates in increasingly complex CPUs make it more difficult to keep the clock signal in phase (synchronized) throughout the entire unit.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This has led many modern CPUs to require multiple identical clock signals to be provided to avoid delaying a single signal significantly enough to cause the CPU to malfunction.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Another major issue, as clock rates increase dramatically, is the amount of heat that is dissipated by the CPU.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The constantly changing clock causes many components to switch regardless of whether they are being used at that time.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] In general, a component that is switching uses more energy than an element in a static state.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Therefore, as clock rate increases, so does energy consumption, causing the CPU to require more heat dissipation in the form of CPU cooling solutions.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] One method of dealing with the switching of unneeded components is called clock gating, which involves turning off the clock signal to unneeded components (effectively disabling them).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] However, this is often regarded as difficult to implement and therefore does not see common usage outside of very low-power designs.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] One notable CPU design that uses extensive clock gating is the IBM PowerPC-based Xenon used in the Xbox 360; this reduces the power requirements of the Xbox 360.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Another method of addressing some of the problems with a global clock signal is the removal of the clock signal altogether.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] While removing the global clock signal makes the design process considerably more complex in many ways, asynchronous (or clockless) designs carry marked advantages in power consumption and heat dissipation in comparison with similar synchronous designs.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] While somewhat uncommon, entire asynchronous CPUs have been built without using a global clock signal.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Two notable examples of this are the ARM compliant AMULET and the MIPS R3000 compatible MiniMIPS.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Rather than totally removing the clock signal, some CPU designs allow certain portions of the device to be asynchronous, such as using asynchronous ALUs in conjunction with superscalar pipelining to achieve some arithmetic performance gains.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] While it is not altogether clear whether totally asynchronous designs can perform at a comparable or better level than their synchronous counterparts, it is evident that they do at least excel in simpler math operations.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This, combined with their excellent power consumption and heat dissipation properties, makes them very suitable for embedded computers.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Many modern CPUs have a die-integrated power managing module which regulates on-demand voltage supply to the CPU circuitry allowing it to keep balance between performance and power consumption.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Every CPU represents numerical values in a specific way.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, some early digital computers represented numbers as familiar decimal (base 10) numeral system values, and others have employed more unusual representations such as bi-quinary coded decimal (base 2–5) or ternary (base 3).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Nearly all modern CPUs represent numbers in binary form, with each digit being represented by some two-valued physical quantity such as a "high" or "low" voltage.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Related to numeric representation is the size and precision of integer numbers that a CPU can represent.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] In the case of a binary CPU, this is measured by the number of bits (significant digits of a binary encoded integer) that the CPU can process in one operation, which is commonly called *word size*, *bit width*, *data path width*, *integer precision*, or *integer size*.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] A CPU's integer size determines the range of integer values on which it can directly operate.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, an 8-bit CPU can directly manipulate integers represented by eight bits, which have a range of 256 (28) discrete integer values.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Integer range can also affect the number of memory locations the CPU can directly address (an address is an integer value representing a specific memory location).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, if a binary CPU uses 32 bits to represent a memory address then it can directly address 232 memory locations.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] To circumvent this limitation and for various other reasons, some CPUs use mechanisms (such as memory management or bank switching) that allow additional memory to be addressed.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] CPUs with larger word sizes require more circuitry and consequently are physically larger, cost more and consume more power (and therefore generate more heat).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] As a result, smaller 4- or 8-bit microcontrollers are commonly used in modern applications even though CPUs with much larger word sizes (such as 16, 32, 64, even 128-bit) are available.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] When higher performance is required, however, the benefits of a larger word size (larger data ranges and address spaces) may outweigh the disadvantages.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] A CPU can have internal data paths shorter than the word size to reduce size and cost.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] To gain some of the advantages afforded by both lower and higher bit lengths, many instruction sets have different bit widths for integer and floating-point data, allowing CPUs implementing that instruction set to have different bit widths for different portions of the device.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, the IBM System/360 instruction set was primarily 32 bit, but supported 64-bit floating-point values to facilitate greater accuracy and range in floating-point numbers.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The System/360 Model 65 had an 8-bit adder for decimal and fixed-point binary arithmetic and a 60-bit adder for floating-point arithmetic.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Many later CPU designs use similar mixed bit width, especially when the processor is meant for general-purpose use where a reasonable balance of integer and floating-point capability is required.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The description of the basic operation of a CPU offered in the previous section describes the simplest form that a CPU can take.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This type of CPU, usually referred to as *subscalar*, operates on and executes one instruction on one or two pieces of data at a time, that is less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This process gives rise to an inherent inefficiency in subscalar CPUs.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Since only one instruction is executed at a time, the entire CPU must wait for that instruction to complete before proceeding to the next instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] As a result, the subscalar CPU gets "hung up" on instructions which take more than one clock cycle to complete execution.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Even adding a second execution unit (see below) does not improve performance much; rather than one pathway being hung up, now two pathways are hung up and the number of unused transistors is increased.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This design, wherein the CPU's execution resources can operate on only one instruction at a time, can only possibly reach *scalar* performance (one instruction per clock cycle, IPC = 1).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] However, the performance is nearly always subscalar (less than one instruction per clock cycle, IPC < 1).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Attempts to achieve scalar and better performance have resulted in a variety of design methodologies that cause the CPU to behave less linearly and more in parallel.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Each methodology differs both in the ways in which they are implemented, as well as the relative effectiveness they afford in increasing the CPU's performance for an application.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] One of the simplest methods for increased parallelism is to begin the first steps of instruction fetching and decoding before the prior instruction finishes executing.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This is a technique known as instruction pipelining, and is used in almost all modern general-purpose CPUs.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Pipelining allows multiple instructions to be executed at a time by breaking the execution pathway into discrete stages.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This separation can be compared to an assembly line, in which an instruction is made more complete at each stage until it exits the execution pipeline and is retired.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Pipelining does, however, introduce the possibility for a situation where the result of the previous operation is needed to complete the next operation; a condition often termed data dependency conflict.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Therefore, pipelined processors must check for these sorts of conditions and delay a portion of the pipeline if necessary.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] A pipelined processor can become very nearly scalar, inhibited only by pipeline stalls (an instruction spending more than one clock cycle in a stage).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Improvements in instruction pipelining led to further decreases in the idle time of CPU components.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Designs that are said to be superscalar include a long instruction pipeline and multiple identical execution units, such as load–store units, arithmetic–logic units, floating-point units and address generation units.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] In a superscalar pipeline, instructions are read and passed to a dispatcher, which decides whether or not the instructions can be executed in parallel (simultaneously).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] If so, they are dispatched to execution units, resulting in their simultaneous execution.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] In general, the number of instructions that a superscalar CPU will complete in a cycle is dependent on the number of instructions it is able to dispatch simultaneously to execution units.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Most of the difficulty in the design of a superscalar CPU architecture lies in creating an effective dispatcher.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The dispatcher needs to be able to quickly determine whether instructions can be executed in parallel, as well as dispatch them in such a way as to keep as many execution units busy as possible.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This requires that the instruction pipeline is filled as often as possible and requires significant amounts of CPU cache.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] It also makes hazard-avoiding techniques like branch prediction, speculative execution, register renaming, out-of-order execution and transactional memory crucial to maintaining high levels of performance.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] By attempting to predict which branch (or path) a conditional instruction will take, the CPU can minimize the number of times that the entire pipeline must wait until a conditional instruction is completed.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Speculative execution often provides modest performance increases by executing portions of code that may not be needed after a conditional operation completes.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Out-of-order execution somewhat rearranges the order in which instructions are executed to reduce delays due to data dependencies.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] When a fraction of the CPU is superscalar, the part that is not suffers a performance penalty due to scheduling stalls.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The Intel P5 Pentium had two superscalar ALUs which could accept one instruction per clock cycle each, but its FPU could not.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Thus the P5 was integer superscalar but not floating point superscalar.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Intel's successor to the P5 architecture, P6, added superscalar abilities to its floating-point features.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Simple pipelining and superscalar design increase a CPU's ILP by allowing it to execute instructions at rates surpassing one instruction per clock cycle.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Most modern CPU designs are at least somewhat superscalar, and nearly all general purpose CPUs designed in the last decade are superscalar.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] In later years some of the emphasis in designing high-ILP computers has been moved out of the CPU's hardware and into its software interface, or instruction set architecture (ISA).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The strategy of the very long instruction word (VLIW) causes some ILP to become implied directly by the software, reducing the CPU's work in boosting ILP and thereby reducing design complexity.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Another strategy of achieving performance is to execute multiple threads or processes in parallel.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This area of research is known as parallel computing.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] In Flynn's taxonomy, this strategy is known as multiple instruction stream, multiple data stream (MIMD).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] One technology used for this purpose is multiprocessing (MP).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The initial type of this technology is known as symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), where a small number of CPUs share a coherent view of their memory system.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] In this scheme, each CPU has additional hardware to maintain a constantly up-to-date view of memory.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] By avoiding stale views of memory, the CPUs can cooperate on the same program and programs can migrate from one CPU to another.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] To increase the number of cooperating CPUs beyond a handful, schemes such as non-uniform memory access (NUMA) and directory-based coherence protocols were introduced in the 1990s.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] SMP systems are limited to a small number of CPUs while NUMA systems have been built with thousands of processors.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Initially, multiprocessing was built using multiple discrete CPUs and boards to implement the interconnect between the processors.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] When the processors and their interconnect are all implemented on a single chip, the technology is known as chip-level multiprocessing (CMP) and the single chip as a multi-core processor.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] It was later recognized that finer-grain parallelism existed with a single program.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] A single program might have several threads (or functions) that could be executed separately or in parallel.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Some of the earliest examples of this technology implemented input/output processing such as direct memory access as a separate thread from the computation thread.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] A more general approach to this technology was introduced in the 1970s when systems were designed to run multiple computation threads in parallel.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This technology is known as multi-threading (MT).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The approach is considered more cost-effective than multiprocessing, as only a small number of components within a CPU are replicated to support MT as opposed to the entire CPU in the case of MP.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] In MT, the execution units and the memory system including the caches are shared among multiple threads.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The downside of MT is that the hardware support for multithreading is more visible to software than that of MP and thus supervisor software like operating systems have to undergo larger changes to support MT.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] One type of MT that was implemented is known as temporal multithreading, where one thread is executed until it is stalled waiting for data to return from external memory.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] In this scheme, the CPU would then quickly context switch to another thread which is ready to run, the switch often done in one CPU clock cycle, such as the UltraSPARC T1.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Another type of MT is simultaneous multithreading, where instructions from multiple threads are executed in parallel within one CPU clock cycle.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] For several decades from the 1970s to early 2000s, the focus in designing high performance general purpose CPUs was largely on achieving high ILP through technologies such as pipelining, caches, superscalar execution, out-of-order execution, etc.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This trend culminated in large, power-hungry CPUs such as the Intel Pentium 4.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] By the early 2000s, CPU designers were thwarted from achieving higher performance from ILP techniques due to the growing disparity between CPU operating frequencies and main memory operating frequencies as well as escalating CPU power dissipation owing to more esoteric ILP techniques.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] CPU designers then borrowed ideas from commercial computing markets such as transaction processing, where the aggregate performance of multiple programs, also known as throughput computing, was more important than the performance of a single thread or process.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This reversal of emphasis is evidenced by the proliferation of dual and more core processor designs and notably, Intel's newer designs resembling its less superscalar P6 architecture.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] A less common but increasingly important paradigm of processors (and indeed, computing in general) deals with data parallelism.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The processors discussed earlier are all referred to as some type of scalar device.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] As the name implies, vector processors deal with multiple pieces of data in the context of one instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This contrasts with scalar processors, which deal with one piece of data for every instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Using Flynn's taxonomy, these two schemes of dealing with data are generally referred to as *single instruction* stream, *multiple data* stream (SIMD) and *single instruction* stream, *single data* stream (SISD), respectively.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The great utility in creating processors that deal with vectors of data lies in optimizing tasks that tend to require the same operation (for example, a sum or a dot product) to be performed on a large set of data.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Some classic examples of these types of tasks include multimedia applications (images, video and sound), as well as many types of scientific and engineering tasks.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Whereas a scalar processor must complete the entire process of fetching, decoding and executing each instruction and value in a set of data, a vector processor can perform a single operation on a comparatively large set of data with one instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This is only possible when the application tends to require many steps which apply one operation to a large set of data.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Most early vector processors, such as the Cray-1, were associated almost exclusively with scientific research and cryptography applications.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] However, as multimedia has largely shifted to digital media, the need for some form of SIMD in general-purpose processors has become significant.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Shortly after inclusion of floating-point units started to become commonplace in general-purpose processors, specifications for and implementations of SIMD execution units also began to appear for general-purpose processors in the mid-1990s.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Some of these early SIMD specifications – like HP's Multimedia Acceleration eXtensions (MAX) and Intel's MMX – were integer-only.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This proved to be a significant impediment for some software developers, since many of the applications that benefit from SIMD primarily deal with floating-point numbers.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Progressively, developers refined and remade these early designs into some of the common modern SIMD specifications, which are usually associated with one instruction set architecture (ISA).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Some notable modern examples include Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE) and the PowerPC-related AltiVec (also known as VMX).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Many modern architectures (including embedded ones) often include hardware performance counters (HPC), which enables low-level (instruction-level) collection, benchmarking, debugging or analysis of running software metrics.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] HPC may also be used to discover and analyze unusual or suspicious activity of the software, such as return-oriented programming (ROP) or sigreturn-oriented programming (SROP) exploits etc.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This is usually done by software-security teams to assess and find malicious binary programs.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Many major vendors (such as IBM, Intel, AMD, and Arm) provide software interfaces (usually written in C/C++) that can be used to collect data from the CPU's registers in order to get metrics.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Operating system vendors also provide software like `perf` (Linux) to record, benchmark, or trace CPU events running kernels and applications.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Hardware counters provide a low-overhead method for collecting comprehensive performance metrics related to a CPU's core elements (functional units, caches, main memory, etc.) – a significant advantage over software profilers.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Additionally, they generally eliminate the need to modify the underlying source code of a program.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Because hardware designs differ between architectures, the specific types and interpretations of hardware counters will also change.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Most modern CPUs have privileged modes to support operating systems and virtualization.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Cloud computing can use virtualization to provide a **virtual central processing unit** (**vCPU**) for separate users; vCPU is not to be confused with a virtual private server (VPS).
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] A host is the virtual equivalent of a physical machine, on which a virtual system is operating.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] When there are several physical machines operating in tandem and managed as a whole, the grouped computing and memory resources form a cluster.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] In some systems, it is possible to dynamically add and remove from a cluster.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Resources available at a host and cluster level can be partitioned into resources pools with fine granularity.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The *performance* or *speed* of a processor depends on, among many other factors, the clock rate (generally given in multiples of hertz) and the instructions per clock (IPC), which together are the factors for the instructions per second (IPS) that the CPU can perform.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Many reported IPS values have represented "peak" execution rates on artificial instruction sequences with few branches, whereas realistic workloads consist of a mix of instructions and applications, some of which take longer to execute than others.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] The performance of the memory hierarchy also greatly affects processor performance, an issue barely considered in IPS calculations.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Because of these problems, various standardized tests, often called "benchmarks" for this purpose – such as SPECint – have been developed to attempt to measure the real effective performance in commonly used applications.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Processing performance of computers is increased by using multi-core processors, which essentially is plugging two or more individual processors (called *cores* in this sense) into one integrated circuit.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Ideally, a dual core processor would be nearly twice as powerful as a single core processor.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] In practice, the performance gain is far smaller, only about 50%, due to imperfect software algorithms and implementation.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Increasing the number of cores in a processor (i.e. dual-core, quad-core, etc.) increases the workload that can be handled.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This means that the processor can now handle numerous asynchronous events, interrupts, etc. which can take a toll on the CPU when overwhelmed.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] These cores can be thought of as different floors in a processing plant, with each floor handling a different task.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Sometimes, these cores will handle the same tasks as cores adjacent to them if a single core is not enough to handle the information.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Multi-core CPUs enhance a computer's ability to run several tasks simultaneously by providing additional processing power.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] However, the increase in speed is not directly proportional to the number of cores added.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] This is because the cores need to interact through specific channels, and this inter-core communication consumes a portion of the available processing speed.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Due to specific capabilities of modern CPUs, such as simultaneous multithreading and uncore, which involve sharing of actual CPU resources while aiming at increased utilization, monitoring performance levels and hardware use gradually became a more complex task.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] As a response, some CPUs implement additional hardware logic that monitors actual use of various parts of a CPU and provides various counters accessible to software; an example is Intel's *Performance Counter Monitor* technology.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Overclocking is a process of increasing the clock speed of a CPU (and other components) beyond their rated speeds.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Increasing a component's clock rate causes it to perform more operations per second.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Overclocking might increase CPU temperature and cause it to overheat, so most users do not overclock and leave the clock speed unchanged.
[src:computer-architecture/central-processing-unit-p02] Manufacturers may limit the degree to which a component can be overclocked, such as by limiting clock ratios, maximum power consumption, or both.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] In computer science and computer engineering, a **computer architecture** is the conceptual design and operational structure of a computer system that define how component parts are organized and interact to execute programs efficiently.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] It is often a general description that ignores precise implementation details.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] It covers the instruction set architecture, CPU microarchitecture, memory, and input/output systems.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Computer architecture also considers tradeoffs between performance, cost, power, reliability, and security.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] The first documented computer architecture was in the correspondence between Charles Babbage and Ada Lovelace, describing the analytical engine.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] While building the computer Z1 in 1936, Konrad Zuse described in two patent applications for his future projects that machine instructions could be stored in the same storage used for data, i.e., the stored-program concept.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] The term "architecture" in computer literature can be traced to the work of Lyle R.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Brooks, Jr., members of the Machine Organization department in IBM's main research center in 1959.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Johnson had the opportunity to write a proprietary research communication about the Stretch, an IBM-developed supercomputer for Los Alamos National Laboratory (at the time known as Los Alamos Scientific Laboratory).
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] To describe the level of detail for discussing the luxuriously embellished computer, he noted that his description of formats, instruction types, hardware parameters, and speed enhancements were at the level of "system architecture", a term that seemed more useful than "machine organization".
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Brooks went on to help develop the IBM System/360 line of computers, in which "architecture" became a noun defining "what the user needs to know".
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] The System/360 line was succeeded by several compatible lines of computers, including the current IBM Z line.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Later, computer users came to use the term in many less explicit ways.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] The earliest computer architectures were designed on paper and then directly built into the final hardware form.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Later, computer architecture prototypes were physically built in the form of a transistor–transistor logic (TTL) computer—such as the prototypes of the 6800 and the PA-RISC—tested, and tweaked, before committing to the final hardware form.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] As of the 1990s, new computer architectures are typically "built", tested, and tweaked—inside some other computer architecture in a computer architecture simulator; or inside a FPGA as a soft microprocessor; or both—before committing to the final hardware form.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] There are other technologies in computer architecture.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Computer architecture is concerned with balancing the performance, efficiency, cost, and reliability of a computer system.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] The case of instruction set architecture can be used to illustrate the balance of these competing factors.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] More complex instruction sets enable programmers to write more space efficient programs, since a single instruction can encode some higher-level abstraction (such as the x86 Loop instruction).
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] However, longer and more complex instructions take longer for the processor to decode and can be more costly to implement effectively.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] The increased complexity from a large instruction set also creates more room for unreliability when instructions interact in unexpected ways.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] The implementation involves integrated circuit design, packaging, power, and cooling.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Optimization of the design requires familiarity with topics from compilers and operating systems to logic design and packaging.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] An instruction set architecture (ISA) is the interface between the computer's software and hardware and also can be viewed as the programmer's view of the machine.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Computers do not understand high-level programming languages such as Java, C++, or most programming languages used.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] A processor only understands instructions encoded in some numerical fashion, usually as binary numbers.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Software tools, such as compilers, translate those high level languages into instructions that the processor can understand.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Besides instructions, the ISA defines items in the computer that are available to a program—e.g., data types, registers, addressing modes, and memory.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Instructions locate these available items with register indexes (or names) and memory addressing modes.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] The ISA of a computer is usually described in a small instruction manual, which describes how the instructions are encoded.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Also, it may define short (vaguely) mnemonic names for the instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] The names can be recognized by a software development tool called an assembler.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] An assembler is a computer program that translates a human-readable form of the ISA into a computer-readable form.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Disassemblers are also widely available, usually in debuggers and software programs to isolate and correct malfunctions in binary computer programs.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Memory organization defines how instructions interact with the memory, and how memory interacts with itself.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] During design emulation, emulators can run programs written in a proposed instruction set.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Modern emulators can measure size, cost, and speed to determine whether a particular ISA is meeting its goals.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Computer organization helps optimize performance-based products.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] For example, software engineers need to know the processing power of processors.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] They may need to optimize software in order to gain the most performance for the lowest price.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] This can require quite a detailed analysis of the computer's organization.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] For example, in an SD card, the designers might need to arrange the card so that the most data can be processed in the fastest possible way.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Computer organization also helps plan the selection of a processor for a particular project.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Multimedia projects may need very rapid data access, while virtual machines may need fast interrupts.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Sometimes certain tasks need additional components as well.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] For example, a computer capable of running a virtual machine needs virtual memory hardware so that the memory of different virtual computers can be kept separated.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Computer organization and features also affect power consumption and processor cost.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Once an instruction set and microarchitecture have been designed, a practical machine must be developed.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] This design process is called the *implementation*.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Implementation is usually not considered architectural design, but rather hardware design engineering.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] For CPUs, the entire implementation process is organized differently and is often referred to as CPU design.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] The exact form of a computer system depends on the constraints and goals.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Computer architectures usually trade off standards, power versus performance, cost, memory capacity, latency (latency is the amount of time that it takes for information from one node to travel to the source) and throughput.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Sometimes other considerations, such as features, size, weight, reliability, and expandability are also factors.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] The most common scheme does an in-depth power analysis and figures out how to keep power consumption low while maintaining adequate performance.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Modern computer performance is often described in instructions per cycle (IPC), which measures the efficiency of the architecture at any clock frequency; a higher IPC means the computer can do more work per unit of time.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Older computers had IPC counts as low as 0.1 while modern processors easily reach nearly 1.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Superscalar processors may reach three to five IPC by executing several instructions per clock cycle.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Counting machine-language instructions would be misleading because they can do varying amounts of work in different ISAs.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] The "instruction" in the standard measurements is not a count of the ISA's machine-language instructions, but a unit of measurement, usually based on the speed of the VAX computer architecture.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Many people used to measure a computer's speed by the clock rate (usually in MHz or GHz).
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] This refers to the cycles per second of the main clock of the CPU.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] However, this metric is somewhat misleading, as a machine with a higher clock rate may not necessarily have greater performance.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] As a result, manufacturers have moved away from clock speed as a measure of performance.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Other factors influence speed, such as the mix of functional units, bus speeds, available memory, and the type and order of instructions in the programs.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] There are two main types of speed: latency and throughput.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Latency is the time between the start of a process and its completion.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Throughput is the amount of work done per unit time.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Interrupt latency is the guaranteed maximum response time of the system to an electronic event (like when the disk drive finishes moving some data).
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Performance is affected by a very wide range of design choices — for example, pipelining a processor usually makes latency worse, but makes throughput better.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Computers that control machinery usually need low interrupt latencies.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] These computers operate in a real-time environment and fail if an operation is not completed in a specified amount of time.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] For example, computer-controlled anti-lock brakes must begin braking within a predictable and limited time period after the brake pedal is sensed or else failure of the brake will occur.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Benchmarking takes all these factors into account by measuring the time a computer takes to run through a series of test programs.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Although benchmarking shows strengths, it should not be how you choose a computer.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Often the measured machines split on different measures.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] For example, one system might handle scientific applications quickly, while another might render video games more smoothly.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Furthermore, designers may target and add special features to their products, through hardware or software, that permit a specific benchmark to execute quickly but do not offer similar advantages to general tasks.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Power efficiency is another important measurement in modern computers.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Higher power efficiency can often be traded for lower speed or higher cost.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Historically, the typical measurement when referring to power consumption in computer architecture was MIPS/W (millions of instructions per second per watt), though modern designs use more sophisticated measurements such as performance-per-watt benchmarks and energy-per-instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Modern integrated circuits consume more total power despite improvements in per-transistor energy efficiency achieved through process scaling.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] This increase stems from the rapid growth in transistor count per die, which demands increasingly complex power delivery networks.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Additionally, power density (watts per unit area) rises as feature sizes (e.g., transistor size) shrink, making thermal management more challenging.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Elevated operating temperatures further complicate these thermal challenges by increasing interconnect resistance, creating a positive feedback loop between power consumption and heat generation.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] As transistor scaling has slowed and power constraints have become limiting factors, power efficiency is starting to become as important, if not more important than fitting more and more transistors into a single chip.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Recent processor designs have shown this emphasis as they put more focus on power efficiency rather than cramming as many transistors into a single chip as possible.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] In the world of embedded computers, power efficiency has long been an important goal next to throughput and latency.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Increases in clock frequency have grown more slowly over the past few years, compared to power reduction improvements.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] This has been driven by the end of Moore's Law and demand for longer battery life and reductions in size for mobile technology.
[src:computer-architecture/computer-architecture] Comparing this to the processing speed increase of 3 GHz to 4 GHz (2002 to 2006), it can be seen that the focus in research and development is shifting away from clock frequency and moving towards consuming less power and taking up less space.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] A **CPU cache** is a hardware cache used by the central processing unit (CPU) of a computer to reduce the average cost (time or energy) to access data from the main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] A cache is a smaller, faster memory, located closer to a processor core, which stores copies of the data from frequently used main memory locations, avoiding the need to always refer to main memory which may be tens to hundreds of times slower to access.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Cache memory is typically implemented with static random-access memory (SRAM), which requires multiple transistors to store a single bit.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] This makes it expensive in terms of the area it takes up, and in modern CPUs the cache is typically the largest part by chip area.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The size of the cache needs to be balanced with the general desire for smaller chips which cost less.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Some modern designs implement some or all of their cache using the physically smaller eDRAM, which is slower to use than SRAM but allows larger amounts of cache for any given amount of chip area.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Most CPUs have a hierarchy of multiple cache levels (L1, L2, often L3, and rarely even L4), with separate instruction-specific (I-cache) and data-specific (D-cache) caches at level 1.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The different levels are implemented in different areas of the chip; L1 is located as close to a CPU core as possible and thus offers the highest speed due to short signal paths, but requires careful design.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] L2 caches are physically separate from the CPU and operate slower, but place fewer demands on the chip designer and can be made much larger without impacting the CPU design.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] L3 caches are generally shared among multiple CPU cores.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Other types of caches exist (that are not counted towards the "cache size" of the most important caches mentioned above), such as the translation lookaside buffer (TLB) which is part of the memory management unit (MMU) which most CPUs have.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Input/output sections also often contain data buffers that serve a similar purpose.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] To access data in main memory, a multi-step process is used and each step introduces a delay.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] For instance, to read a value from memory in a simple computer system the CPU first selects the address to be accessed by expressing it on the address bus and waiting a fixed time to allow the value to settle.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The memory device with that value, normally implemented in DRAM, holds that value in a very low-energy form that is not powerful enough to be read directly by the CPU.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Instead, it has to copy that value from storage into a small buffer which is connected to the data bus.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] It then waits a certain time to allow this value to settle before reading the value from the data bus.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] By locating the memory physically closer to the CPU the time needed for the buses to settle is reduced, and by replacing the DRAM with SRAM, which hold the value in a form that does not require amplification to be read, the delay within the memory itself is eliminated.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] This makes the cache much faster both to respond and to read or write.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] SRAM, however, requires anywhere from four to six transistors to hold a single bit, depending on the type, whereas DRAM generally uses one transistor and one capacitor per bit, which makes it able to store much more data for any given chip area.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Implementing some memory in a faster format can lead to large performance improvements.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] When trying to read from or write to a location in the memory, the processor checks whether the data from that location is already in the cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] If so, the processor will read from or write to the cache instead of the much slower main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Used to speed up virtual-to-physical address translation for both executable instructions and data.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] A single TLB can be provided for access to both instructions and data, or a separate Instruction TLB (ITLB) and data TLB (DTLB) can be provided.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] (MMU) and not directly related to the CPU caches.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Early examples of CPU caches include the Atlas 2 and the IBM System/360 Model 85 in the 1960s.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The first CPUs that used a cache had only one level of cache; unlike later level 1 cache, it was not split into L1d (for data) and L1i (for instructions).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Split L1 cache started in 1976 with the IBM 801 CPU, became mainstream in the late 1980s, and in 1997 entered the embedded CPU market with the ARMv5TE.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] As of 2015, even sub-dollar SoCs split the L1 cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The L2 cache is usually not split, and acts as a common repository for the already split L1 cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Every core of a multi-core processor has a dedicated L1 cache and is usually not shared between the cores.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The L2 cache, and lower-level caches, may be shared between the cores.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] L4 cache is currently uncommon, and is generally dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) on a separate die or chip, rather than static random-access memory (SRAM).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] An exception to this is when eDRAM is used for all levels of cache, down to L1.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Historically L1 was also on a separate die, however bigger die sizes have allowed integration of it as well as other cache levels, with the possible exception of the last level.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Each extra level of cache tends to be smaller and faster than the lower levels.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Caches (like for RAM historically) have generally been sized in powers of: 2, 4, 8, 16 etc.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] KiB; when up to MiB sizes (i.e. for larger non-L1), very early on the pattern broke down, to allow for larger caches without being forced into the doubling-in-size paradigm, with e.g.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Intel Core 2 Duo with 3 MiB L2 cache in April 2008.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] This happened much later for L1 caches, as their size is generally still a small number of KiB.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] In 2020, some Intel Atom CPUs (with up to 24 cores) have (multiple of) 4.5 MiB and 15 MiB cache sizes.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Data is transferred between memory and cache in blocks of fixed size, called *cache lines* or *cache blocks*.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] When a cache line is copied from memory into the cache, a cache entry is created.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The cache entry will include the copied data as well as the requested memory location (called a tag).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] When the processor needs to read or write a location in memory, it first checks for a corresponding entry in the cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The cache checks for the contents of the requested memory location in any cache lines that might contain that address.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] If the processor finds that the memory location is in the cache, a **cache hit** has occurred.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] However, if the processor does not find the memory location in the cache, a **cache miss** has occurred.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] In the case of a cache hit, the processor immediately reads or writes the data in the cache line.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] For a cache miss, the cache allocates a new entry and copies data from main memory, then the request is fulfilled from the contents of the cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] To make room for the new entry on a cache miss, the cache may have to evict one of the existing entries.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The heuristic it uses to choose the entry to evict is called the replacement policy.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The fundamental problem with any replacement policy is that it must predict which existing cache entry is least likely to be used in the future.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Predicting the future is generally difficult, so there is no perfect method to choose among the variety of replacement policies available.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] One popular replacement policy, least-recently used (LRU), replaces the least recently accessed entry.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Marking some memory ranges as non-cacheable can improve performance, by avoiding caching of memory regions that are rarely re-accessed.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] This avoids the overhead of loading something into the cache without having any reuse.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Cache entries may also be disabled or locked depending on the context.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] If data are written to the cache, at some point they must also be written to main memory; the timing of this write is known as the write policy.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] In a write-through cache, every write to the cache causes a write to main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Alternatively, in a write-back or copy-back cache, writes are not immediately mirrored to the main memory, with locations been written over being marked as dirty, being written back to the main memory only when they are evicted from the cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may sometimes require two memory accesses to service: one to first write the dirty location to main memory, and then another to read the new location from memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Also, a write to a main memory location that is not yet mapped in a write-back cache may evict an already dirty location, thereby freeing that cache space for the new memory location.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] There are intermediate policies as well.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The cache may be write-through, but the writes may be held in a store data queue temporarily, usually so multiple stores can be processed together (which can reduce bus turnarounds and improve bus utilization).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Cached data from the main memory may be changed by other entities (e.g., peripherals using direct memory access (DMA) or another core in a multi-core processor), in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or stale.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Alternatively, when a CPU in a multiprocessor system updates data in the cache, copies of data in caches associated with other CPUs become stale.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are known as cache coherence protocols.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Cache performance measurement has become important in recent times where the speed gap between the memory performance and the processor performance is increasing exponentially.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The cache was introduced to reduce this speed gap.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Thus knowing how well the cache is able to bridge the gap in the speed of processor and memory becomes important, especially in high-performance systems.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The cache hit rate and the cache miss rate play an important role in determining this performance.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] To improve the cache performance, reducing the miss rate becomes one of the necessary steps among other steps.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Decreasing the access time to the cache also gives a boost to its performance and helps with optimization.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The time taken to fetch one cache line from memory (read latency due to a cache miss) matters because the CPU will run out of work while waiting for the cache line.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] When a CPU reaches this state, it is called a stall.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] As CPUs become faster compared to main memory, stalls due to cache misses displace more potential computation; modern CPUs can execute hundreds of instructions in the time taken to fetch a single cache line from main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Various techniques have been employed to keep the CPU busy during this time, including out-of-order execution in which the CPU attempts to execute independent instructions after the instruction that is waiting for the cache miss data.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Another technology, used by many processors, is simultaneous multithreading (SMT), which allows an alternate thread to use the CPU core while the first thread waits for required CPU resources to become available.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The placement policy decides where in the cache a copy of a particular entry of main memory will go.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] If the placement policy is free to choose any entry in the cache to hold the copy, the cache is called *fully associative*.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] At the other extreme, if each entry in the main memory can go in just one place in the cache, the cache is *direct-mapped*.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Many caches implement a compromise in which each entry in the main memory can go to any one of N places in the cache, and are described as N-way set associative.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] For example, the level-1 data cache in an AMD Athlon is two-way set associative, which means that any particular location in main memory can be cached in either of two locations in the level-1 data cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Choosing the right value of associativity involves a trade-off.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] If there are ten places to which the placement policy could have mapped a memory location, then to check if that location is in the cache, ten cache entries must be searched.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Checking more places takes more power and chip area, and potentially more time.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] On the other hand, caches with more associativity suffer fewer misses (see conflict misses), so that the CPU wastes less time reading from the slow main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The general guideline is that doubling the associativity, from direct mapped to two-way, or from two-way to four-way, has about the same effect on raising the hit rate as doubling the cache size.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] However, increasing associativity more than four does not improve hit rate as much, and are generally done for other reasons (see virtual aliasing).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Some CPUs can dynamically reduce the associativity of their caches in low-power states, which acts as a power-saving measure.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] In this cache organization, each location in the main memory can go in only one entry in the cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Therefore, a direct-mapped cache can also be called a "one-way set associative" cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] It does not have a placement policy as such, since there is no choice of which cache entry's contents to evict.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] This means that if two locations map to the same entry, they may continually knock each other out.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Although simpler, a direct-mapped cache needs to be much larger than an associative one to give comparable performance, and it is more unpredictable.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Let x be block number in cache, y be block number of memory, and n be number of blocks in cache, then mapping is done with the help of the equation *x* = *y* mod *n*.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] One benefit of this scheme is that the tags stored in the cache do not have to include that part of the main memory address which is implied by the cache memory's index.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Since the cache tags have fewer bits, they require fewer transistors, take less space on the processor circuit board or on the microprocessor chip, and can be read and compared faster.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Also LRU algorithm is especially simple since only one bit needs to be stored for each pair.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] One of the advantages of a direct-mapped cache is that it allows simple and fast speculation.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Once the address has been computed, the one cache index which might have a copy of that location in memory is known.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] That cache entry can be read, and the processor can continue to work with that data before it finishes checking that the tag actually matches the requested address.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The idea of having the processor use the cached data before the tag match completes can be applied to associative caches as well.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] A subset of the tag, called a *hint*, can be used to pick just one of the possible cache entries mapping to the requested address.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The entry selected by the hint can then be used in parallel with checking the full tag.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The hint technique works best when used in the context of address translation, as explained below.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Other schemes have been suggested, such as the *skewed cache*, where the index for way 0 is direct, as above, but the index for way 1 is formed with a hash function.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] A good hash function has the property that addresses which conflict with the direct mapping tend not to conflict when mapped with the hash function, and so it is less likely that a program will suffer from an unexpectedly large number of conflict misses due to a pathological access pattern.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The downside is extra latency from computing the hash function.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Additionally, when it comes time to load a new line and evict an old line, it may be difficult to determine which existing line was least recently used, because the new line conflicts with data at different indexes in each way; LRU tracking for non-skewed caches is usually done on a per-set basis.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Nevertheless, skewed-associative caches have major advantages over conventional set-associative ones.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] A true set-associative cache tests all the possible ways simultaneously, using something like a content-addressable memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] A pseudo-associative cache tests each possible way one at a time.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] A hash-rehash cache and a column-associative cache are examples of a pseudo-associative cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] In the common case of finding a hit in the first way tested, a pseudo-associative cache is as fast as a direct-mapped cache, but it has a much lower conflict miss rate than a direct-mapped cache, closer to the miss rate of a fully associative cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Comparing with a direct-mapped cache, a set associative cache has a reduced number of bits for its cache set index that maps to a cache set, where multiple ways or blocks stays, such as 2 blocks for a 2-way set associative cache and 4 blocks for a 4-way set associative cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Comparing with a direct mapped cache, the unused cache index bits become a part of the tag bits.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] For example, a 2-way set associative cache contributes 1 bit to the tag and a 4-way set associative cache contributes 2 bits to the tag.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The basic idea of the multicolumn cache is to use the set index to map to a cache set as a conventional set associative cache does, and to use the added tag bits to index a way in the set.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] For example, in a 4-way set associative cache, the two bits are used to index way 00, way 01, way 10, and way 11, respectively.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] This double cache indexing is called a "major location mapping", and its latency is equivalent to a direct-mapped access.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Extensive experiments in multicolumn cache design shows that the hit ratio to major locations is as high as 90%.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] If cache mapping conflicts with a cache block in the major location, the existing cache block will be moved to another cache way in the same set, which is called "selected location".
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Because the newly indexed cache block is a most recently used (MRU) block, it is placed in the major location in multicolumn cache with a consideration of temporal locality.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Since multicolumn cache is designed for a cache with a high associativity, the number of ways in each set is high; thus, it is easy find a selected location in the set.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] A selected location index by an additional hardware is maintained for the major location in a cache block.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Multicolumn cache remains a high hit ratio due to its high associativity, and has a comparable low latency to a direct-mapped cache due to its high percentage of hits in major locations.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The *data block* (cache line) contains the actual data fetched from the main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The *tag* contains (part of) the address of the actual data fetched from the main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The "size" of the cache is the amount of main memory data it can hold.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] This size can be calculated as the number of bytes stored in each data block times the number of blocks stored in the cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] An effective memory address which goes along with the cache line (memory block) is split (MSB to LSB) into the tag, the index and the block offset.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The index describes which cache set that the data has been put in.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The index length is $\lceil \log _{2}(s)\rceil$ bits for s cache sets.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The block offset specifies the desired data within the stored data block within the cache row.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Typically the effective address is in bytes, so the block offset length is $\lceil \log _{2}(b)\rceil$ bits, where b is the number of bytes per data block.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The tag contains the most significant bits of the address, which are checked against all rows in the current set (the set has been retrieved by index) to see if this set contains the requested address.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Some authors refer to the block offset as simply the "offset" or the "displacement".
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The original Pentium 4 processor had a four-way set associative L1 data cache of 8 KiB in size, with 64-byte cache blocks.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Hence, there are 8 KiB / 64 = 128 cache blocks.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The number of sets is equal to the number of cache blocks divided by the number of ways of associativity, what leads to 128 / 4 = 32 sets, and hence 25 = 32 different indices.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Since the CPU address is 32 bits wide, this implies 32 − 5 − 6 = 21 bits for the tag field.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The original Pentium 4 processor also had an eight-way set associative L2 integrated cache 256 KiB in size, with 128-byte cache blocks.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] This implies 32 − 8 − 7 = 17 bits for the tag field.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] An instruction cache requires only one flag bit per cache row entry: a valid bit.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The valid bit indicates whether or not a cache block has been loaded with valid data.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] On power-up, the hardware sets all the valid bits in all the caches to "invalid".
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Some systems also set a valid bit to "invalid" at other times, such as when multi-master bus snooping hardware in the cache of one processor hears an address broadcast from some other processor, and realizes that certain data blocks in the local cache are now stale and should be marked invalid.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] A data cache typically requires two flag bits per cache line – a valid bit and a dirty bit.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Having a dirty bit set indicates that the associated cache line has been changed since it was read from main memory ("dirty"), meaning that the processor has written data to that line and the new value has not propagated all the way to main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] A cache miss is a failed attempt to read or write a piece of data in the cache, which results in a main memory access with much longer latency.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] There are three kinds of cache misses: instruction read miss, data read miss, and data write miss.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Most general purpose CPUs implement some form of virtual memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] To summarize, either each program running on the machine sees its own simplified address space, which contains code and data for that program only, or all programs run in a common virtual address space.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] A program executes by calculating, comparing, reading and writing to addresses of its virtual address space, rather than addresses of physical address space, making programs simpler and thus easier to write.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Virtual memory requires the processor to translate virtual addresses generated by the program into physical addresses in main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The portion of the processor that does this translation is known as the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The fast path through the MMU can perform those translations stored in the translation lookaside buffer (TLB), which is a cache of mappings from the operating system's page table, segment table, or both.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] One early virtual memory system, the IBM M44/44X, required an access to a mapping table held in core memory before every programmed access to main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] With no caches, and with the mapping table memory running at the same speed as main memory this effectively cut the speed of memory access in half.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Two early machines that used a page table in main memory for mapping, the IBM System/360 Model 67 and the GE 645, both had a small associative memory as a cache for accesses to the in-memory page table.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Both machines predated the first machine with a cache for main memory, the IBM System/360 Model 85, so the first hardware cache used in a computer system was not a data or instruction cache, but rather a TLB.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The speed of this recurrence (the *load latency*) is crucial to CPU performance, and so most modern level-1 caches are virtually indexed, which at least allows the MMU's TLB lookup to proceed in parallel with fetching the data from the cache RAM.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] But virtual indexing is not the best choice for all cache levels.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The cost of dealing with virtual aliases grows with cache size, and as a result most level-2 and larger caches are physically indexed.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Caches have historically used both virtual and physical addresses for the cache tags, although virtual tagging is now uncommon.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] If the TLB lookup can finish before the cache RAM lookup, then the physical address is available in time for tag compare, and there is no need for virtual tagging.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Large caches, then, tend to be physically tagged, and only small, very low latency caches are virtually tagged.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] In recent general-purpose CPUs, virtual tagging has been superseded by virtual hints, as described below.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] A cache that relies on virtual indexing and tagging becomes inconsistent after the same virtual address is mapped into different physical addresses (homonym), which can be solved by using physical address for tagging, or by storing the address space identifier in the cache line.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] However, the latter approach does not help against the synonym problem, in which several cache lines end up storing data for the same physical address.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Writing to such locations may update only one location in the cache, leaving the others with inconsistent data.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] This issue may be solved by using non-overlapping memory layouts for different address spaces, or otherwise the cache (or a part of it) must be flushed when the mapping changes.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The great advantage of virtual tags is that, for associative caches, they allow the tag match to proceed before the virtual to physical translation is done.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] However, coherence probes and evictions present a physical address for action.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The hardware must have some means of converting the physical addresses into a cache index, generally by storing physical tags as well as virtual tags.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] For comparison, a physically tagged cache does not need to keep virtual tags, which is simpler.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] When a virtual to physical mapping is deleted from the TLB, cache entries with those virtual addresses will have to be flushed somehow.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Alternatively, if cache entries are allowed on pages not mapped by the TLB, then those entries will have to be flushed when the access rights on those pages are changed in the page table.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] It is also possible for the operating system to ensure that no virtual aliases are simultaneously resident in the cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The operating system makes this guarantee by enforcing page coloring, which is described below.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Some early RISC processors (SPARC, RS/6000) took this approach.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] It has not been used recently, as the hardware cost of detecting and evicting virtual aliases has fallen and the software complexity and performance penalty of perfect page coloring has risen.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] It can be useful to distinguish the two functions of tags in an associative cache: they are used to determine which way of the entry set to select, and they are used to determine if the cache hit or missed.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The second function must always be correct, but it is permissible for the first function to guess, and get the wrong answer occasionally.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Some processors (e.g. early SPARCs) have caches with both virtual and physical tags.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The virtual tags are used for way selection, and the physical tags are used for determining hit or miss.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] This kind of cache enjoys the latency advantage of a virtually tagged cache, and the simple software interface of a physically tagged cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] It bears the added cost of duplicated tags, however.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Also, during miss processing, the alternate ways of the cache line indexed have to be probed for virtual aliases and any matches evicted.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The extra area (and some latency) can be mitigated by keeping *virtual hints* with each cache entry instead of virtual tags.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] These hints are a subset or hash of the virtual tag, and are used for selecting the way of the cache from which to get data and a physical tag.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Like a virtually tagged cache, there may be a virtual hint match but physical tag mismatch, in which case the cache entry with the matching hint must be evicted so that cache accesses after the cache fill at this address will have just one hint match.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Since virtual hints have fewer bits than virtual tags distinguishing them from one another, a virtually hinted cache suffers more conflict misses than a virtually tagged cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Perhaps the ultimate reduction of virtual hints can be found in the Pentium 4 (Willamette and Northwood cores).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] In these processors the virtual hint is effectively two bits, and the cache is four-way set associative.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Effectively, the hardware maintains a simple permutation from virtual address to cache index, so that no content-addressable memory (CAM) is necessary to select the right one of the four ways fetched.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Large physically indexed caches (usually secondary caches) run into a problem: the operating system rather than the application controls which pages collide with one another in the cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Differences in page allocation from one program run to the next lead to differences in the cache collision patterns, which can lead to very large differences in program performance.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] These differences can make it very difficult to get a consistent and repeatable timing for a benchmark run.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] To understand the problem, consider a CPU with a 1 MiB physically indexed direct-mapped level-2 cache and 4 KiB virtual memory pages.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Sequential physical pages map to sequential locations in the cache until after 256 pages the pattern wraps around.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] We can label each physical page with a color of 0–255 to denote where in the cache it can go.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Locations within physical pages with different colors cannot conflict in the cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Programmers attempting to make maximum use of the cache may arrange their programs' access patterns so that only 1 MiB of data need be cached at any given time, thus avoiding capacity misses.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] But they should also ensure that the access patterns do not have conflict misses.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] One way to think about this problem is to divide up the virtual pages the program uses and assign them virtual colors in the same way as physical colors were assigned to physical pages before.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Programmers can then arrange the access patterns of their code so that no two pages with the same virtual color are in use at the same time.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] There is a wide literature on such optimizations (e.g. loop nest optimization), largely coming from the High Performance Computing (HPC) community.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The snag is that while all the pages in use at any given moment may have different virtual colors, some may have the same physical colors.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] In fact, if the operating system assigns physical pages to virtual pages randomly and uniformly, it is extremely likely that some pages will have the same physical color, and then locations from those pages will collide in the cache (this is the birthday paradox).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The solution is to have the operating system attempt to assign different physical color pages to different virtual colors, a technique called *page coloring*.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Although the actual mapping from virtual to physical color is irrelevant to system performance, odd mappings are difficult to keep track of and have little benefit, so most approaches to page coloring simply try to keep physical and virtual page colors the same.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] If the operating system can guarantee that each physical page maps to only one virtual color, then there are no virtual aliases, and the processor can use virtually indexed caches with no need for extra virtual alias probes during miss handling.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] Alternatively, the OS can flush a page from the cache whenever it changes from one virtual color to another.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] As mentioned above, this approach was used for some early SPARC and RS/6000 designs.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] The software page coloring technique has been used to effectively partition the shared Last level Cache (LLC) in multicore processors.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p01] This operating system-based LLC management in multicore processors has been adopted by Intel.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Modern processors have multiple interacting on-chip caches.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The operation of a particular cache can be completely specified by the cache size, the cache block size, the number of blocks in a set, the cache set replacement policy, and the cache write policy (write-through or write-back).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] While all of the cache blocks in a particular cache are the same size and have the same associativity, typically the "higher-level" caches (called Level 1 cache) have a smaller number of blocks, smaller block size, and fewer blocks in a set, but have very short access times.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Level 2 and below) have progressively larger numbers of blocks, larger block size, more blocks in a set, and relatively longer access times, but are still much faster than main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Cache entry replacement policy is determined by a cache algorithm selected to be implemented by the processor designers.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] In some cases, multiple algorithms are provided for different kinds of work loads.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Pipelined CPUs access memory from multiple points in the pipeline: instruction fetch, virtual-to-physical address translation, and data fetch (see classic RISC pipeline).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The natural design is to use different physical caches for each of these points, so that no one physical resource has to be scheduled to service two points in the pipeline.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Thus the pipeline naturally ends up with at least three separate caches (instruction, TLB, and data), each specialized to its particular role.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] A **victim cache** is a cache used to hold blocks evicted from a CPU cache upon replacement.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The victim cache lies between the main cache and its refill path, and holds only those blocks of data that were evicted from the main cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The victim cache is usually fully associative, and is intended to reduce the number of conflict misses.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Many commonly used programs do not require an associative mapping for all the accesses.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] In fact, only a small fraction of the memory accesses of the program require high associativity.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The victim cache exploits this property by providing high associativity to only these accesses.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] It was introduced by Norman Jouppi from DEC in 1990.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Intel's *Crystalwell* variant of its Haswell processors introduced an on-package 128 MiB eDRAM Level 4 cache which serves as a victim cache to the processors' Level 3 cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] In the Skylake microarchitecture the Level 4 cache no longer works as a victim cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] One of the more extreme examples of cache specialization is the **trace cache** (also known as *execution trace cache*) found in the Intel Pentium 4 microprocessors.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] A trace cache is a mechanism for increasing the instruction fetch bandwidth and decreasing power consumption (in the case of the Pentium 4) by storing traces of instructions that have already been fetched and decoded.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] A trace cache stores instructions either after they have been decoded, or as they are retired.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Generally, instructions are added to trace caches in groups representing either individual basic blocks or dynamic instruction traces.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The Pentium 4's trace cache stores micro-operations resulting from decoding x86 instructions, providing also the functionality of a micro-operation cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Having this, the next time an instruction is needed, it does not have to be decoded into micro-ops again.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Write Coalescing Cache is a special cache that is part of L2 cache in AMD's Bulldozer microarchitecture.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Stores from both L1D caches in the module go through the WCC, where they are buffered and coalesced.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The WCC's task is reducing number of writes to the L2 cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] A **micro-operation cache** (**μop cache**, **uop cache** or **UC**) is a specialized cache that stores micro-operations of decoded instructions, as received directly from the instruction decoders or from the instruction cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] When an instruction needs to be decoded, the μop cache is checked for its decoded form which is re-used if cached; if it is not available, the instruction is decoded and then cached.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] One of the early works describing μop cache as an alternative frontend for the Intel P6 processor family is the 2001 paper *"Micro-Operation Cache: A Power Aware Frontend for Variable Instruction Length ISA"*.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Later, Intel included μop caches in its Sandy Bridge processors and in successive microarchitectures like Ivy Bridge and Haswell.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] AMD implemented a μop cache in their Zen microarchitecture.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Fetching complete pre-decoded instructions eliminates the need to repeatedly decode variable length complex instructions into simpler fixed-length micro-operations, and simplifies the process of predicting, fetching, rotating and aligning fetched instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] A μop cache effectively offloads the fetch and decode hardware, thus decreasing power consumption and improving the frontend supply of decoded micro-operations.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The μop cache also increases performance by more consistently delivering decoded micro-operations to the backend and eliminating various bottlenecks in the CPU's fetch and decode logic.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] A μop cache has many similarities with a trace cache, although a μop cache is much simpler thus providing better power efficiency; this makes it better suited for implementations on battery-powered devices.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The main disadvantage of the trace cache, leading to its power inefficiency, is the hardware complexity required for its heuristic deciding on caching and reusing dynamically created instruction traces.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] A **branch target cache** or **branch target instruction cache**, the name used on ARM microprocessors, is a specialized cache which holds the first few instructions at the destination of a taken branch.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] This is used by low-powered processors which do not need a normal instruction cache because the memory system is capable of delivering instructions fast enough to satisfy the CPU without one.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] However, this only applies to consecutive instructions in sequence; it still takes several cycles of latency to restart instruction fetch at a new address, causing a few cycles of pipeline bubble after a control transfer.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] A branch target cache provides instructions for those few cycles avoiding a delay after most taken branches.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] This allows full-speed operation with a much smaller cache than a traditional full-time instruction cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Smart Cache shares the actual cache memory between the cores of a multi-core processor.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] In comparison to a dedicated per-core cache, the overall cache miss rate decreases when cores do not require equal parts of the cache space.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Consequently, a single core can use the full level 2 or level 3 cache while the other cores are inactive.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Furthermore, the shared cache makes it faster to share memory among different execution cores.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Another issue is the fundamental tradeoff between cache latency and hit rate.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Larger caches have better hit rates but longer latency.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] To address this tradeoff, many computers use multiple levels of cache, with small fast caches backed up by larger, slower caches.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Multi-level caches generally operate by checking the fastest but smallest cache, *level 1* (**L1**), first; if it hits, the processor proceeds at high speed.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] If that cache misses, the slower but larger next level cache, *level 2* (**L2**), is checked, and so on, before accessing external memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] As the latency difference between main memory and the fastest cache has become larger, some processors have begun to utilize as many as three levels of on-chip cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Price-sensitive designs used this to pull the entire cache hierarchy on-chip, but by the 2010s some of the highest-performance designs returned to having large off-chip caches, which is often implemented in eDRAM and mounted on a multi-chip module, as a fourth cache level.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] In rare cases, such as in the mainframe CPU IBM z15 (2019), all levels down to L1 are implemented by eDRAM, replacing SRAM entirely (for cache, SRAM is still used for registers).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Apple's ARM-based Apple silicon series, starting with the A14 and M1, have a 192 KiB L1i cache for each of the high-performance cores, an unusually large amount; however the high-efficiency cores only have 128 KiB.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Since then other processors such as Intel's Lunar Lake and Qualcomm's Oryon have also implemented similar L1i cache sizes.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The benefits of L3 and L4 caches depend on the application's access patterns.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] However, with register renaming most compiler register assignments are reallocated dynamically by hardware at runtime into a register bank, allowing the CPU to break false data dependencies and thus easing pipeline hazards.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Register files sometimes also have hierarchy: The Cray-1 (circa 1976) had eight address "A" and eight scalar data "S" registers that were generally usable.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] There was also a set of 64 address "B" and 64 scalar data "T" registers that took longer to access, but were faster than main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The "B" and "T" registers were provided because the Cray-1 did not have a data cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] When considering a chip with multiple cores, there is a question of whether the caches should be shared or local to each core.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Implementing shared cache inevitably introduces more wiring and complexity.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] But then, having one cache per *chip*, rather than *core*, greatly reduces the amount of space needed, and thus one can include a larger cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Typically, sharing the L1 cache is undesirable because the resulting increase in latency would make each core run considerably slower than a single-core chip.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] For example, an eight-core chip with three levels may include an L1 cache for each core, one intermediate L2 cache for each pair of cores, and one L3 cache shared between all cores.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] A shared highest-level cache (usually L3, called before accessing memory), is usually referred to as a *last-level cache* (LLC).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Additional techniques are used for increasing the level of parallelism when LLC is shared between multiple cores, including slicing it into multiple pieces which are addressing certain ranges of memory addresses, and can be accessed independently.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] In a separate cache structure, instructions and data are cached separately, meaning that a cache line is used to cache either instructions or data, but not both; various benefits have been demonstrated with separate data and instruction translation lookaside buffers.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] In a unified structure, this constraint is not present, and cache lines can be used to cache both instructions and data.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Multi-level caches introduce new design decisions.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] For instance, in some processors, all data in the L1 cache must also be somewhere in the L2 cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] These caches are called *strictly inclusive*.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Other processors (like the AMD Athlon) have *exclusive* caches: data are guaranteed to be in at most one of the L1 and L2 caches, never in both.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Still other processors (like the Intel Pentium II, III, and 4) do not require that data in the L1 cache also reside in the L2 cache, although it may often do so.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] There is no universally accepted name for this intermediate policy; two common names are "non-exclusive" and "partially-inclusive".
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The advantage of exclusive caches is that they store more data.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] This advantage is larger when the exclusive L1 cache is comparable to the L2 cache, and diminishes if the L2 cache is many times larger than the L1 cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] When the L1 misses and the L2 hits on an access, the hitting cache line in the L2 is exchanged with a line in the L1.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] This exchange is quite a bit more work than just copying a line from L2 to L1, which is what an inclusive cache does.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] One advantage of strictly inclusive caches is that when external devices or other processors in a multiprocessor system wish to remove a cache line from the processor, they need only have the processor check the L2 cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] In cache hierarchies which do not enforce inclusion, the L1 cache must be checked as well.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] As a drawback, there is a correlation between the associativities of L1 and L2 caches: if the L2 cache does not have at least as many ways as all L1 caches together, the effective associativity of the L1 caches is restricted.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Another disadvantage of inclusive cache is that whenever there is an eviction in L2 cache, the (possibly) corresponding lines in L1 also have to get evicted in order to maintain inclusiveness.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] This is quite a bit of work, and would result in a higher L1 miss rate.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Another advantage of inclusive caches is that the larger cache can use larger cache lines, which reduces the size of the secondary cache tags.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Scratchpad memory (SPM), also known as scratchpad, scratchpad RAM or local store in computer terminology, is a high-speed internal memory used for temporary storage of calculations, data, and other work in progress.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] To illustrate both specialization and multi-level caching, here is the cache hierarchy of the K8 core in the AMD Athlon 64 CPU.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The K8 has four specialized caches: an instruction cache, an instruction TLB, a data TLB, and a data cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] There are second-level instruction and data TLBs, which store only PTEs mapping 4 KiB.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Both instruction and data caches, and the various TLBs, can fill from the large **unified** L2 cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] This cache is exclusive to both the L1 instruction and data caches, which means that any 8-byte line can only be in one of the L1 instruction cache, the L1 data cache, or the L2 cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] It is, however, possible for a line in the data cache to have a PTE which is also in one of the TLBs—the operating system is responsible for keeping the TLBs coherent by flushing portions of them when the page tables in memory are updated.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The K8 also caches information that is never stored in memory—prediction information.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] These caches are not shown in the above diagram.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] As is usual for this class of CPU, the K8 has fairly complex branch prediction, with tables that help predict whether branches are taken and other tables which predict the targets of branches and jumps.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Some of this information is associated with instructions, in both the level 1 instruction cache and the unified secondary cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The K8 uses an interesting trick to store prediction information with instructions in the secondary cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Lines in the secondary cache are protected from accidental data corruption (e.g. by an alpha particle strike) by either ECC or parity, depending on whether those lines were evicted from the data or instruction primary caches.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Since the parity code takes fewer bits than the ECC code, lines from the instruction cache have a few spare bits.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] These bits are used to cache branch prediction information associated with those instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The net result is that the branch predictor has a larger effective history table, and so has better accuracy.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Other processors have other kinds of predictors (e.g., the store-to-load bypass predictor in the DEC Alpha 21264).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] These predictors are caches in that they store information that is costly to compute.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Some of the terminology used when discussing predictors is the same as that for caches (one speaks of a **hit** in a branch predictor), but predictors are not generally thought of as part of the cache hierarchy.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The K8 keeps the instruction and data caches **coherent** in hardware, which means that a store into an instruction closely following the store instruction will change that following instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Other processors, like those in the Alpha and MIPS family, have relied on software to keep the instruction cache coherent.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Stores are not guaranteed to show up in the instruction stream until a program calls an operating system facility to ensure coherency.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] In computer engineering, a *tag RAM* is used to specify which of the possible memory locations is currently stored in a CPU cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] For a simple, direct-mapped design fast SRAM can be used.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Higher associative caches usually employ content-addressable memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Cache **reads** are the most common CPU operation that takes more than a single cycle.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Program execution time tends to be very sensitive to the latency of a level-1 data cache hit.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] A great deal of design effort, and often power and silicon area are expended making the caches as fast as possible.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The simplest cache is a virtually indexed direct-mapped cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The virtual address is calculated with an adder, the relevant portion of the address extracted and used to index an SRAM, which returns the loaded data.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The data are byte aligned in a byte shifter, and from there are bypassed to the next operation.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] There is no need for any tag checking in the inner loop – in fact, the tags need not even be read.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Later in the pipeline, but before the load instruction is retired, the tag for the loaded data must be read, and checked against the virtual address to make sure there was a cache hit.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] On a miss, the cache is updated with the requested cache line and the pipeline is restarted.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] An associative cache is more complicated, because some form of tag must be read to determine which entry of the cache to select.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] An N-way set-associative level-1 cache usually reads all N possible tags and N data in parallel, and then chooses the data associated with the matching tag.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Level-2 caches sometimes save power by reading the tags first, so that only one data element is read from the data SRAM.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The adjacent diagram is intended to clarify the manner in which the various fields of the address are used.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Address bit 31 is most significant, bit 0 is least significant.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The diagram shows the SRAMs, indexing, and multiplexing for a 4 KiB, 2-way set-associative, virtually indexed and virtually tagged cache with 64 byte (B) lines, a 32-bit read width and 32-bit virtual address.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Because the cache is 4 KiB and has 64 B lines, there are just 64 lines in the cache, and we read two at a time from a Tag SRAM which has 32 rows, each with a pair of 21 bit tags.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Although any function of virtual address bits 31 through 6 could be used to index the tag and data SRAMs, it is simplest to use the least significant bits.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Similarly, because the cache is 4 KiB and has a 4 B read path, and reads two ways for each access, the Data SRAM is 512 rows by 8 bytes wide.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] A more modern cache might be 16 KiB, 4-way set-associative, virtually indexed, virtually hinted, and physically tagged, with 32 B lines, 32-bit read width and 36-bit physical addresses.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The read path recurrence for such a cache looks very similar to the path above.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Instead of tags, virtual hints are read, and matched against a subset of the virtual address.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Later on in the pipeline, the virtual address is translated into a physical address by the TLB, and the physical tag is read (just one, as the virtual hint supplies which way of the cache to read).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Finally the physical address is compared to the physical tag to determine if a hit has occurred.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Some SPARC designs have improved the speed of their L1 caches by a few gate delays by collapsing the virtual address adder into the SRAM decoders.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The early history of cache technology is closely tied to the invention and use of virtual memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Because of scarcity and cost of semi-conductor memories, early mainframe computers in the 1960s used a complex hierarchy of physical memory, mapped onto a flat virtual memory space used by programs.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The memory technologies would span semi-conductor, magnetic core, drum and disc.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Virtual memory seen and used by programs would be flat and caching would be used to fetch data and instructions into the fastest memory ahead of processor access.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Extensive studies were done to optimize the cache sizes.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Optimal values were found to depend greatly on the programming language used with Algol needing the smallest and Fortran and Cobol needing the largest cache sizes.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] In the early days of microcomputer technology, memory access was only slightly slower than register access.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] But since the 1980s the performance gap between processor and memory has been growing.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Microprocessors have advanced much faster than memory, especially in terms of their operating frequency, so memory became a performance bottleneck.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] While it was technically possible to have all the main memory as fast as the CPU, a more economically viable path has been taken: use plenty of low-speed memory, but also introduce a small high-speed cache memory to alleviate the performance gap.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] This provided an order of magnitude more capacity—for the same price—with only a slightly reduced combined performance.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The first documented uses of a TLB were on the GE 645 and the IBM 360/67, both of which used an associative memory as a TLB.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The first documented use of an instruction cache was on the CDC 6600.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The first documented use of a data cache was on the IBM System/360 Model 85.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The 68010, released in 1982, has a "loop mode" which can be considered a tiny and special-case instruction cache that accelerates loops that consist of only two instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The 68020, released in 1984, replaced that with a typical instruction cache of 256 bytes, being the first 68k series processor to feature true on-chip cache memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The 68030, released in 1987, is basically a 68020 core with an additional 256-byte data cache, an on-chip memory management unit (MMU), a process shrink, and added burst mode for the caches.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The 68040, released in 1990, has split instruction and data caches of four kilobytes each.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The 68060, released in 1994, has the following: 8 KiB data cache (four-way associative), 8 KiB instruction cache (four-way associative), 96-byte FIFO instruction buffer, 256-entry branch cache, and 64-entry address translation cache MMU buffer (four-way associative).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] As the x86 microprocessors reached clock rates of 20 MHz and above in the 386, small amounts of fast cache memory began to be featured in systems to improve performance.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] This was because the DRAM used for main memory had significant latency, up to 120 ns, as well as refresh cycles.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The cache was constructed from more expensive, but significantly faster, SRAM memory cells, which at the time had latencies around 10–25 ns.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The early caches were external to the processor and typically located on the motherboard in the form of eight or nine DIP devices placed in sockets to enable the cache as an optional extra or upgrade feature.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Some versions of the Intel 386 processor could support 16 to 256 KiB of external cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] With the 486 processor, an 8 KiB cache was integrated directly into the CPU die.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] This cache was termed Level 1 or L1 cache to differentiate it from the slower on-motherboard, or Level 2 (L2) cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] These on-motherboard caches were much larger, with the most common size being 256 KiB.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] There were some system boards that contained sockets for the Intel 485Turbocache daughtercard which had either 64 or 128 Kbyte of cache memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The popularity of on-motherboard cache continued through the Pentium MMX era but was made obsolete by the introduction of SDRAM and the growing disparity between bus clock rates and CPU clock rates, which caused on-motherboard cache to be only slightly faster than main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The next development in cache implementation in the x86 microprocessors began with the Pentium Pro, which brought the secondary cache onto the same package as the microprocessor, clocked at the same frequency as the microprocessor.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] On-motherboard caches enjoyed prolonged popularity thanks to the AMD K6-2 and AMD K6-III processors that still used Socket 7, which was previously used by Intel with on-motherboard caches.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] K6-III included 256 KiB on-die L2 cache and took advantage of the on-board cache as a third level cache, named L3 (motherboards with up to 2 MiB of on-board cache were produced).
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] After the Socket 7 became obsolete, on-motherboard cache disappeared from the x86 systems.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The three-level caches were used again first with the introduction of the Intel Xeon MP "Foster Core", where the L3 cache was added to the CPU die.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] It became common for the total cache sizes to be increasingly larger in newer processor generations, and recently (as of 2011) it is not uncommon to find Level 3 cache sizes of tens of megabytes.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Intel introduced a Level 4 on-package cache with the Haswell microarchitecture.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] *Crystalwell* Haswell CPUs, equipped with the GT3e variant of Intel's integrated Iris Pro graphics, effectively feature 128 MiB of embedded DRAM (eDRAM) on the same package.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] This L4 cache is shared dynamically between the on-die GPU and CPU, and serves as a victim cache to the CPU's L3 cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The Apple M1 CPU has 128 or 192 KiB of L1 instruction cache for each core (important for latency/single-thread performance), depending on core type.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] This is an unusually large L1 cache for any CPU type (not just for a laptop); the total cache memory size is not unusually large (the total is more important for throughput) for a laptop, and much larger total (e.g.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] L3 or L4) sizes are available in IBM's mainframes.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Early cache designs focused entirely on the direct cost of cache and RAM and average execution speed.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] More recent cache designs also consider energy efficiency, fault tolerance, and other goals.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] There are several tools available to computer architects to help explore tradeoffs between the cache cycle time, energy, and area; the CACTI cache simulator and the SimpleScalar instruction set simulator are two open-source options.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] A multi-ported cache is a cache which can serve more than one request at a time.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] When accessing a traditional cache we normally use a single memory address, whereas in a multi-ported cache we may request N addresses at a time – where N is the number of ports that connected through the processor and the cache.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] The benefit of this is that a pipelined processor may access memory from different phases in its pipeline.
[src:computer-architecture/cpu-cache-p02] Another benefit is that it allows the concept of super-scalar processors through different cache levels.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] The **Harvard architecture** is a computer architecture with separate storage and signal pathways for instructions and data.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] It is often contrasted with the von Neumann architecture, where program instructions and data share the same memory and pathways.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] The Harvard architecture is often used in real-time processing or low-power applications.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] The term is often stated as having originated from the Harvard Mark I relay-based computer, which stored instructions on punched tape (24 bits wide) and data in electro-mechanical counters.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] These early machines had data storage entirely contained within the central processing unit, and provided no access to the instruction storage as data.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] Programs needed to be loaded by an operator; the processor could not initialize itself.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] The concept of the Harvard architecture has been questioned by some researchers.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] Modern processors appear to the user to be systems with von Neumann architectures, with the program code stored in the same main memory as the data.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] For performance reasons, internally and largely invisible to the user, most designs have separate processor caches for the instructions and data, with separate pathways into the processor for each.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] This is one form of what is known as the modified Harvard architecture.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] Harvard architecture is historically, and traditionally, split into two address spaces, but having three, i.e. two extra (and all accessed in each cycle) is also done, while rare.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] In a Harvard architecture, there is no need to make the two memories share characteristics.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] In particular, the word width, timing, implementation technology, and memory address structure can differ.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] In some systems, instructions for pre-programmed tasks can be stored in read-only memory while data memory generally requires read-write memory.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] In some systems, there is much more instruction memory than data memory so instruction addresses are wider than data addresses.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] In a system with a pure von Neumann architecture, instructions and data are stored in the same memory, so instructions are fetched over the same data path used to fetch data.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] This means that a CPU cannot simultaneously read an instruction and read or write data from or to the memory.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] In a computer using the Harvard architecture, the CPU can both read an instruction and perform a data memory access at the same time, even without a cache.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] A Harvard architecture computer can thus be faster for a given circuit complexity because instruction fetches and data access do not contend for a single memory pathway.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] Also, a Harvard architecture machine has distinct code and data address spaces: instruction address zero is not the same as data address zero.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] Instruction address zero might identify a twenty-four-bit value, while data address zero might indicate an eight-bit byte that is not part of that twenty-four-bit value.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] A modified Harvard architecture machine is very much like a Harvard architecture machine, but it relaxes the strict separation between instruction and data while still letting the CPU concurrently access two (or more) memory buses.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] The most common modification includes separate instruction and data caches backed by a common address space.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] While the CPU executes from cache, it acts as a pure Harvard machine.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] When accessing backing memory, it acts like a von Neumann machine (where code can be moved around like data, which is a powerful technique).
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] This modification is widespread in modern processors, such as the ARM architecture, Power ISA and x86 processors.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] It is sometimes loosely called a Harvard architecture, overlooking the fact that it is actually "modified".
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] Another modification provides a pathway between the instruction memory (such as ROM or flash memory) and the CPU to allow words from the instruction memory to be treated as read-only data.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] This technique is used in some microcontrollers, including the Atmel AVR.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] This allows constant data, such as text strings or function tables, to be accessed without first having to be copied into data memory, preserving scarce (and power-hungry) data memory for read/write variables.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] Special machine language instructions are provided to read data from the instruction memory, or the instruction memory can be accessed using a peripheral interface.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] In recent years, the speed of the CPU has grown many times in comparison to the access speed of the main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] Care needs to be taken to reduce the number of times main memory is accessed in order to maintain performance.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] If, for instance, every instruction run in the CPU requires an access to memory, the computer gains nothing for increased CPU speed—a problem referred to as being memory bound.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] It is possible to make extremely fast memory, but this is only practical for small amounts of memory for cost, power and signal routing reasons.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] The solution is to provide a small amount of very fast memory known as a CPU cache which holds recently accessed data.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] As long as the data that the CPU needs is in the cache, the performance is much higher than it is when the CPU has to get the data from the main memory.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] On the other side, however, it may still be limited to storing repetitive programs or data and still has a storage size limitation, and other potential problems associated with it.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] Modern high performance CPU chip designs incorporate aspects of both Harvard and von Neumann architecture.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] In particular, the "split cache" version of the modified Harvard architecture is very common.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] CPU cache memory is divided into an instruction cache and a data cache.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] Harvard architecture is used as the CPU accesses the cache.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] In the case of a cache miss, however, the data is retrieved from the main memory, which is not formally divided into separate instruction and data sections, although it may well have separate memory controllers used for concurrent access to RAM, ROM and (NOR) flash memory.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] Thus, while a von Neumann architecture is visible in some contexts, such as when data and code come through the same memory controller, the hardware implementation gains the efficiencies of the Harvard architecture for cache accesses and at least some main memory accesses.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] In addition, CPUs often have write buffers which let CPUs proceed after writes to non-cached regions.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] The von Neumann nature of memory is then visible when instructions are written as data by the CPU and software must ensure that the caches (data and instruction) and write buffer are synchronized before trying to execute those just-written instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] The principal advantage of the pure Harvard architecture—simultaneous access to more than one memory system—has been reduced by modified Harvard processors using modern CPU cache systems.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] Fairly pure Harvard architecture machines are used mostly in applications where trade-offs, like the cost and power savings from omitting caches, outweigh the programming penalties from featuring distinct code and data address spaces.
[src:computer-architecture/harvard-architecture] Even in these cases, it is common to employ special instructions in order to access program memory as though it were data for read-only tables, or for reprogramming; those processors are modified Harvard architecture processors.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] The **instruction cycle** (also known as the **fetch–decode–execute cycle**, or simply the **fetch–execute cycle**) is the cycle that the central processing unit (CPU) follows from boot-up until the computer has shut down in order to process instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] It is composed of three main stages: the fetch stage, the decode stage, and the execute stage.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] In simpler CPUs, the instruction cycle is executed sequentially, each instruction being processed before the next one is started.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] In most modern CPUs, the instruction cycles are instead executed concurrently, and often in parallel, through an instruction pipeline: the next instruction starts being processed before the previous instruction has finished, which is possible because the cycle is broken up into separate steps.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] The program counter (PC) is a register that holds the memory address of the next instruction to be executed.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] After each instruction copy to the memory address register (MAR), the PC can either increment the pointer to the next sequential instruction, jump to a specified pointer, or branch conditionally to a specified pointer.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] Also, during a CPU halt, the PC holds the instruction being executed, until an external interrupt or a reset signal is received.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] The MAR is responsible for storing the address describing the location of the instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] After a read signal is initiated, the instruction in the address from the MAR is read and placed into the memory data register (MDR), also known as Memory Buffer Register (MBR).
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] This component overall functions as an address buffer for pointing to locations in memory.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] The MDR is responsible for temporarily holding instructions read from the address in MAR.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] It acts as a two-way register in the instruction cycle because it can take output from memory to the CPU, or output from the CPU to memory.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] The current instruction register (CIR, though sometimes referred to as the instruction register, IR) is where the instruction is temporarily held, for the CPU to decode it and produce correct control signals for the execution stage.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] The control unit (CU) decodes the instruction in the current instruction register (CIR).
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] Then, the CU sends signals to other components within the CPU, such as the arithmetic logic unit (ALU), or back to memory to fetch operands, or to the floating-point unit (FPU).
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] The ALU performs arithmetic operations based on specific opcodes in the instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] For example, in RISC-V architecture, funct3 and funct7 opcodes exist to distinguish whether an instruction is a logical or arithmetic operation.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] **Decode stage**: During this stage, the encoded instruction in the CIR is interpreted by the CU.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] It determines what operations and additional operands are required for execution and sends respective signals to respective components within the CPU, such as the ALU or FPU, to prepare for the execution of the instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] **Execute stage**: This is the stage where the actual operation specified by the instruction is carried out by the relevant functional units of the CPU.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] Logical or arithmetic operations may be run by the ALU, data may be read from or written to memory, and the results are stored in registers or memory as required by the instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] Based on output from the ALU, the PC might branch.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] In addition, on most processors, interrupts can occur.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] This will cause the CPU to jump to an interrupt service routine, execute that, and then return to the instruction it was meant to be executing.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] In some cases, the instruction can be interrupted in the middle, but there will be no effect, and the instruction will be re-executed after return from the interrupt.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] This address is copied to the MAR, where this address is used to poll for the location of the instruction in memory.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] The CU sends a signal to the control bus to read the memory at the address in MAR - the data read is placed in the data bus.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] The data is transferred to the CPU via the data bus, where it's loaded into the MDR - at this stage, the PC increments by one.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] The contents (instruction to-be-executed) of the MDR are copied into the CIR (where the instruction opcode and data operand can be decoded).
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] The decoding process allows the processor to determine what instruction is to be performed so that the CPU can tell how many operands it needs to fetch in order to perform the instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] The opcode fetched from the memory is decoded for the next steps and moved to the appropriate registers.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] The decoding is typically performed by binary decoders in the CPU's CU.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] There are various ways that an architecture can specify determining the address for operands, usually called the addressing modes.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] The CPU sends the decoded instruction (decoded from the CU) as a set of control signals to corresponding components.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] This is the only stage of the instruction cycle that is useful from the perspective of the end-user.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-cycle] Everything else is overhead required to make the execute step happen.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] In computer engineering, **instruction pipelining** is a technique for implementing instruction-level parallelism within a single processor.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining attempts to keep every part of the processor busy with some instruction by dividing incoming instructions into a series of sequential steps (the eponymous "pipeline") performed by different processor units with different parts of instructions processed in parallel.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] In a pipelined computer, instructions travel through the central processing unit (CPU) in stages.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] For example, it might have one stage for each step of the von Neumann cycle: Fetch the instruction, fetch the operands, do the instruction, write the results.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] A pipelined computer usually has "pipeline registers" after each stage.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] These store information from the instruction and calculations so that the logic gates of the next stage can do the next step.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] This arrangement lets the CPU complete an instruction on each clock cycle.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] It is common for even-numbered stages to operate on one edge of the square-wave clock, while odd-numbered stages operate on the other edge.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] This allows more CPU throughput than a multicycle computer at a given clock rate, but may increase latency due to the added overhead of the pipelining process itself.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Also, even though the electronic logic has a fixed maximum speed, a pipelined computer can be made faster or slower by varying the number of stages in the pipeline.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] With more stages, each stage does less work, and so the stage has fewer delays from the logic gates and could run at a higher clock rate.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] A pipelined model of computer is often the most economical, when cost is measured as logic gates per instruction per second.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] At each instant, an instruction is in only one pipeline stage, and on average, a pipeline stage is less costly than a multicycle computer.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Also, when made well, most of the pipelined computer's logic is in use most of the time.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] In contrast, out of order computers usually have large amounts of idle logic at any given instant.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Similar calculations usually show that a pipelined computer uses less energy per instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] However, a pipelined computer is usually more complex and more costly than a comparable multicycle computer.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] It typically has more logic gates, registers and a more complex control unit.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] In a like way, it might use more total energy, while using less energy per instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Out of order CPUs can usually do more instructions per second because they can do several instructions at once.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] In a pipelined computer, the control unit arranges for the flow to start, continue, and stop as a program commands.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] The instruction data is usually passed in pipeline registers from one stage to the next, with a somewhat separated piece of control logic for each stage.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] The control unit also assures that the instruction in each stage does not harm the operation of instructions in other stages.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] For example, if two stages must use the same piece of data, the control logic assures that the uses are done in the correct sequence.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] When operating efficiently, a pipelined computer will have an instruction in each stage.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] It is then working on all of those instructions at the same time.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] It can finish about one instruction for each cycle of its clock.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] But when a program switches to a different sequence of instructions, the pipeline sometimes must discard the data in process and restart.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Much of the design of a pipelined computer prevents interference between the stages and reduces stalls.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] The number of dependent steps varies with the machine architecture.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] As the pipeline is made "deeper" (with a greater number of dependent steps), a given step can be implemented with simpler circuitry, which may let the processor clock run faster.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] A processor is said to be *fully pipelined* if it can fetch an instruction on every cycle.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Thus, if some instructions or conditions require delays that inhibit fetching new instructions, the processor is not fully pipelined.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Seminal uses of pipelining were in the ILLIAC II project and the IBM Stretch project, though a simple version was used earlier in the Z1 in 1939 and the Z3 in 1941.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining began in earnest in the late 1970s in supercomputers such as vector processors and array processors.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] One of the early supercomputers was the Cyber series built by Control Data Corporation.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Its main architect, Seymour Cray, later headed Cray Research.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Cray developed the XMP line of supercomputers, using pipelining for both multiply and add/subtract functions.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Later, Star Technologies added parallelism (several pipelined functions working in parallel), developed by Roger Chen.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] In 1984, Star Technologies added the pipelined divide circuit developed by James Bradley.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining was not limited to supercomputers.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] In 1976, the Amdahl Corporation's 470 series general purpose mainframe had a 7-step pipeline, and a patented branch prediction circuit.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] A central element in RISC design philosophy, by the mid-1980s, pipelining was also being introduced into traditional CISC architectures by their developers.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] The model of sequential execution assumes that each instruction completes before the next one begins; this assumption is not true on a pipelined processor.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] A situation where the expected result is problematic is known as a hazard.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] If the processor has the 5 steps listed in the initial illustration (the 'Basic five-stage pipeline' at the start of the article), instruction 1 would be fetched at time *t*1 and its execution would be complete at *t5*.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Instruction 2 would be fetched at *t2* and would be complete at *t6*.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] The first instruction might deposit the incremented number into R5 as its fifth step (register write back) at *t5*.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] But the second instruction might get the number from R5 (to copy to R6) in its second step (instruction decode and register fetch) at time *t3*.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] It seems that the first instruction would not have incremented the value by then.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Writing computer programs in a compiled language might not raise these concerns, as the compiler could be designed to generate machine code that avoids hazards.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] The programmer may have unrelated work that the processor can do in the meantime; or, to ensure correct results, the programmer may insert NOPs into the code, partly negating the advantages of pipelining.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] A branch out of the normal instruction sequence often involves a hazard.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Unless the processor can give effect to the branch in a single time cycle, the pipeline will continue fetching instructions sequentially.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Such instructions cannot be allowed to take effect because the programmer has diverted control to another part of the program.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] A conditional branch is even more problematic.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] The processor may or may not branch, depending on a calculation that has not yet occurred.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Various processors may stall, may attempt branch prediction, and may be able to begin to execute two different program sequences (eager execution), each assuming the branch is or is not taken, discarding all work that pertains to the incorrect guess.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] A processor with an implementation of branch prediction that usually makes correct predictions can minimize the performance penalty from branching.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] However, if branches are predicted poorly, it may create more work for the processor, such as flushing from the pipeline the incorrect code path that has begun execution before resuming execution at the correct location.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Programs written for a pipelined processor deliberately avoid branching to minimize possible loss of speed.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] For example, the programmer can handle the usual case with sequential execution and branch only on detecting unusual cases.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Using programs such as gcov to analyze code coverage lets the programmer measure how often particular branches are actually executed and gain insight with which to optimize the code.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] In some cases, a programmer can handle both the usual case and unusual case with branch-free code.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] can be problematic on a pipelined processor.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] In this technique, one of the effects of a program is to modify its own upcoming instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] and the modification will not take effect.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] can configure their on-chip cache memories for data-only fetches, or as part of their ordinary memory address space, and avoid such difficulties with self-modifying instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] between instructions, but a pipelining processor overlaps instructions, so executing an uninterruptible instruction renders portions of ordinary instructions uninterruptible too.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] a single-core system using an infinite loop in which an uninterruptible instruction was always in the pipeline.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining keeps all portions of the processor occupied and increases the amount of useful work the processor can do in a given time.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Pipelining typically reduces the processor's cycle time and increases the throughput of instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] that require execution to slow below its ideal rate.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] A non-pipelined processor executes only a single instruction at a time.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] The start of the next instruction is delayed not based on hazards but unconditionally.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] A pipelined processor's need to organize all its work into modular steps may require the duplication of registers, which increases the latency of some instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] By making each dependent step simpler, pipelining can enable complex operations more economically than adding complex circuitry, such as for numerical calculations.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] However, a processor that declines to pursue increased speed with pipelining may be simpler and cheaper to manufacture.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Compared to environments where the programmer needs to avoid or work around hazards, use of a non-pipelined processor may make it easier to program and to train programmers.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] The non-pipelined processor also makes it easier to predict the exact timing of a given sequence of instructions.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] To the right is a generic pipeline with four stages: fetch, decode, execute and write-back.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] The top gray box is the list of instructions waiting to be executed, the bottom gray box is the list of instructions that have had their execution completed, and the middle white box is the pipeline.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] A pipelined processor may deal with hazards by stalling and creating a bubble in the pipeline, resulting in one or more cycles in which nothing useful happens.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] In the illustration at right, in cycle 3, the processor cannot decode the purple instruction, perhaps because the processor determines that decoding depends on results produced by the execution of the green instruction.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] The green instruction can proceed to the Execute stage and then to the Write-back stage as scheduled, but the purple instruction is stalled for one cycle at the Fetch stage.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] The blue instruction, which was due to be fetched during cycle 3, is stalled for one cycle, as is the red instruction after it.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Because of the bubble (the blue ovals in the illustration), the processor's Decode circuitry is idle during cycle 3.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] Its Execute circuitry is idle during cycle 4 and its Write-back circuitry is idle during cycle 5.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] When the bubble moves out of the pipeline (at cycle 6), normal execution resumes.
[src:computer-architecture/instruction-pipelining] It will take 8 cycles (cycle 1 through 8) rather than 7 to completely execute the four instructions shown in colors.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] In computer architecture, the **memory hierarchy** separates computer storage into a hierarchy based on response time.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] Since response time, complexity, and capacity are related, the levels may also be distinguished by their performance and controlling technologies.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] Memory hierarchy affects performance in computer architectural design, algorithm predictions, and lower level programming constructs involving locality of reference.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] Designing for high performance requires considering the restrictions of the memory hierarchy, i.e. the size and capabilities of each component.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] Each of the various components can be viewed as part of a hierarchy of memories (*m*1, *m*2, ..., *mn*) in which each member mi is typically smaller and faster than the next highest member *m**i*+1 of the hierarchy.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] To limit waiting by higher levels, a lower level will respond by filling a buffer and then signaling for activating the transfer.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] This is a general memory hierarchy structuring.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] For example, a paging algorithm may be considered as a level for virtual memory when designing a computer architecture, and one can include a level of nearline storage between online and offline storage.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] The number of levels in the memory hierarchy and the performance at each level has increased over time.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] The type of memory or storage components also change historically.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] Some CPUs include additional levels of cache between L3 and memory.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] For example, the Haswell microarchitecture includes an L4 cache of 128 MB on mobile units.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] The lower levels of the hierarchy – from mass storage downwards – are also known as tiered storage.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] For example, always-on spinning disks are online, while spinning disks that spin down, such as massive arrays of idle disk (MAID), are nearline.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] Removable media such as tape cartridges that can be automatically loaded, as in a tape library, are nearline, while cartridges that must be manually loaded are offline.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] Most modern CPUs are so fast that, for most program workloads, the bottleneck is the locality of reference of memory accesses and the efficiency of the caching and memory transfer between different levels of the hierarchy.
[src:computer-architecture/memory-hierarchy] As a result, the CPU spends much of its time idling, waiting for memory I/O to complete.
